d School of Medicine campuses only.</ref>\n| faculty              = Total: 9,835 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=New+York+University&s=all&id=193900#general|title=College Navigator - New York University|website=Nces.ed.gov|accessdate=September 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717181431/https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=new+york+university&s=all&id=193900#general|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><br />(5,723 full-time / <br />4,112 part-time)<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\"/>\n| chairman             = [[William R. Berkley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/board-of-trustees/election-of-william-berkley-stern-66-as-chair-designate-of-the-nyu-board-of-trustees.html|title=The Election of William Berkley, Stern '66, as Chair-Designate of the NYU Board of Trustees|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=September 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911222118/http://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/board-of-trustees/election-of-william-berkley-stern-66-as-chair-designate-of-the-nyu-board-of-trustees.html|archive-date=September 11, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| president            = [[Andrew D. Hamilton]]\n| provost              = [[Katherine Elizabeth Fleming|Katherine E. Fleming]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/office-of-the-provost.html|title=Office of the Provost|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=August 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905235732/http://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/office-of-the-provost.html|archive-date=September 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| students             = 51,848 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"ed.gov\"/>\n| undergrad            = 26,733 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"ed.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/employees/resources-and-services/administrative-services/institutional-research/factbook.html|title=Factbook|website=Nyu.edu|accessdate=19 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103224818/https://www.nyu.edu/employees/resources-and-services/administrative-services/institutional-research/factbook.html|archive-date=January 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| postgrad             = 25,115 (Fall 2018)<ref name=\"ed.gov\"/>\n| city                 = [[New York City|New York]]\n| state                = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postalcode           = 10003\n| country              = United States\n| campus               = [[Urban area|Urban]] {{convert|230|acre|sqkm|adj=on}} <br />(Manhattan campus)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/features/education/3-2-1-college/os-nyu-college-tour-its-a-whole-different-world-20131205-post.html|title=NYU college tour: Great school but very expensive - Orlando Sentinel|author=Orlando Sentinel|date=December 5, 2013|work=OrlandoSentinel.com|access-date=November 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117023216/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/features/education/3-2-1-college/os-nyu-college-tour-its-a-whole-different-world-20131205-post.html|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| athletics            = [[NCAA Division III]] \u2013 [[University Athletic Association|UAA]]\n| colors               = Purple and White<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf|title=New York University Graphic Standards and Logo Usage Guide, second edition, February 2010|publisher=New York University|format=PDF|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114346/https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/cmsTeam/documents/NYUGraphStandards.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><br />{{color box|#57068C}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| mascot               = Bobcat\n| nickname             = [[NYU Violets|Violets]]\n| website              = {{url|nyu.edu}}\n| logo                 = NYU logo.svg\n}}\n\n'''New York University''' ('''NYU''') is a [[private university|private]] [[research university]] based in [[New York City]]. Founded in 1831 by [[Albert Gallatin]] as an institution to \"admit based upon merit rather than birthright or social class\", NYU's historical campus is in [[Greenwich Village]].<ref name=\"Schools and Colleges\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/academics/schools-and-colleges.html|title=Schools and Colleges|last=|first=|date=|website=New York University|publisher=New York University|accessdate=December 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106224856/http://www.nyu.edu/academics/schools-and-colleges.html|archive-date=November 6, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=New York University|title=Mayor Bloomberg: It's hard to differentiate where NYU stops and NYC starts|date=August 15, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sBs_t8L64Is|accessdate=January 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205160242/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sBs_t8L64Is|archive-date=February 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> NYU is tied for 29th among [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] colleges in the United States by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', and 27th in the world by [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|''Times Higher Education'']]. NYU is [[University admission|highly selective]], admitting 15% of more than 85,000 applicants in fall 2019, making NYU the most applied-to private university in the U.S.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/news/2020/04/01/nyu-acceptance-rate-drops-to-15%25-for-class-of-2024/|title=NYU Acceptance Rate Drops to 15% for the Class of 2024 {{!}} Washington Square News|last=Cochran|first=Lisa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/news/2020/02/06/nyu-acceptance-rate-2024/|title=NYU Class of 2024 Applications Exceed 85,000 {{!}} Washington Square News|last=Stallone|first=Cole|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theclassroom.com/colleges-with-the-most-applications-data-study.html|title=Colleges With the Most Applications {{!}} The Classroom|website=The Classroom {{!}} Empowering Students in Their College Journey|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nNYU is the largest independent research university in the United States, but also has degree-granting campuses in [[NYU Abu Dhabi|Abu Dhabi]] and [[NYU Shanghai|Shanghai]], and academic centers in [[Accra]], [[Berlin]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[NYU Florence|Florence]], [[NYU London|London]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Madrid]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], [[Prague]], [[Sydney]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/global/global-academic-centers.html|title=Global Academic Centers|website=New York University|access-date=July 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710022925/http://www.nyu.edu/global/global-academic-centers.html|archive-date=July 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"The Global Network University\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/global/the-global-network-university.html |title=The Global Network University |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=August 30, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825101657/http://www.nyu.edu/global/the-global-network-university.html|archivedate=August 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/november/nyu-to-set-up-a-program-in-los-angeles-for-students-in-the-arts-.html|title=NYU to set up program in Los Angeles|last=Beckman|first=John|date=15 November 2018|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128210915/https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/november/nyu-to-set-up-a-program-in-los-angeles-for-students-in-the-arts-.html|archive-date=November 28, 2018|access-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.princetonreview.com/college/new-york-university-1022976|title=New York University - The Princeton Review College Rankings & Reviews|website=www.princetonreview.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> NYU is organized into 25 schools, including 10 undergraduate school and numerous graduate schools.<ref name=\":2\" /> The university has numerous research efforts, including founding the [[American Chemical Society]] and holding research partnerships with the [[Inception Institute of Artificial Intelligence]] and with major technology firms such as [[Twitter]] and [[IBM]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/about/aboutacs.html|title=ACS Fast Facts|website=American Chemical Society|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tahawultech.com/industry/education/nyu-abu-dhabi-inks-new-deal-to-boost-ai-research/|title=NYU Abu Dhabi inks new deal to boost AI research|date=2020-04-06|website=TahawulTech.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The university has also since launched various internal research centers in the fields of artificial intelligence, history, culture, medicine, mathematics, philosophy, and economics.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smialek|first=Jeanna|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/14/business/nobel-economics.html|title=Nobel Economics Prize Goes to Pioneers in Reducing Poverty|date=2019-10-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> NYU is one of the top feeder schools for careers in finance and investment banking on [[Wall Street]], accounting for 3.9% of hires in major financial institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/top-10-colleges-for-landing-wall-street-job-2018-10|title=These are the top 10 colleges if you want to land a job on Wall Street|last=Shi|first=Madeline|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nNYU is labeled as one of the \"New [[Ivy League|Ivies]]\", and was ranked as America's \"#1 dream school\" by the [[Princeton Review]] from 2004 to 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primecolleges.blogspot.in/2016/05/new-york-university.html|title=Prime Colleges: New York University|author=Satish K|website=Primecolleges.blogspot.in|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816141519/http://primecolleges.blogspot.in/2016/05/new-york-university.html|archive-date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708135928/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/14325172/site/newsweek/|title=America's 25 New Elite 'Ivies' - Kaplan College Guide - MSNBC.com|date=2007-07-08|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/americas-25-new-elite-ivies-108771|title=America's 25 New Elite 'Ivies'|last=EDT|first=Newsweek Staff On 8/20/06 at 8:00 PM|date=2006-08-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The university's [[Medical school in the United States|medical school]], [[New York University School of Medicine|NYU Grossman School of Medicine]], became [[Free education|tuition-free]] to all students in 2018, regardless of need or merit, becoming the only national top 10 medical school (NYU is ranked #4 for research in the nation) in the nation to offer it.<ref name=\"npr.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/08/17/639467023/nyu-medical-school-says-it-will-offer-free-tuition-to-all-students|title=NYU Medical School Plans Free Tuition For Those Studying To Be Doctors|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The university's other graduate schools are also highly ranked, including [[New York University School of Law|NYU School of Law]] as the 6th best [[law school]] in the nation, the [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]] as the 10th best [[business school]] in the nation, the [[New York University Tisch School of the Arts|Tisch School of Arts]] as the 2nd best [[film school]] in the nation, and the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] as the 9th best mathematics school (1st for applied mathematics) in the nation.<ref name=\"npr.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/top-25-american-film-schools-ranked-1231343/item/2019-top-25-film-schools-nyu-1231347|title=NYU - The Top 25 American Film Schools, Ranked|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/correction-nyu-tandon-school-engineering-211702905.html|title=CORRECTION: NYU Tandon School of Engineering continues historic rise in U.S. News & World Report rankings|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> [[New York University College of Arts & Science|NYU's College of Arts and Science]] also holds the 11th best [[economics]] department in the nation, 12th best [[political science]] department in the nation, and the #1 ranked [[philosophy]] department in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2020/philosophy|title=Philosophy|date=2020-02-25|website=Top Universities|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, multiple [[Head of state|heads of state]], [[royalty]], a [[List of justices of the Supreme Court of the United States|US Supreme Court justice]], 5 [[State Governor|State Governors]], 17 [[List of universities by number of billionaire alumni|billionaires]], [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation|37 Nobel Laureates]], [[List of Turing Award laureates by university affiliation|8 Turing Award winners]], [[List of Fields Medal winners by university affiliation|5 Fields Medalists]], 31 [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellows]], 167 [[Guggenheim Fellows]],  3 [[Astronaut|astronauts]], 7 [[Abel Prize]] winners, 7 [[Lasker Award]] winners, a [[Crafoord Prize]] winner, 26 [[Pulitzer Prize]] winners, 37 [[Academy Award]] winners, 30 [[Emmy Award]] winners, 25 [[Tony Award]] winners, 12 [[Grammy Award]] winners, multiple [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 under 30]] and [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]] notables, and hundreds of members of the [[National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine|National Academies of Sciences]], [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], [[United States Congress]], and [[Foreign Service Officer|U.S. diplomats]] have been affiliated with [[List of New York University faculty|faculty]] or [[List of New York University alumni|alumni]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailynous.com/2020/04/09/philosophers-among-new-class-guggenheim-fellows/|title=Philosophers Among New Class of Guggenheim Fellows|last=Weinberg|first=Justin|date=2020-04-09|website=Daily Nous|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100475323|title=Billionaire U: Why Harvard Mints Mega-Rich Alums|last1=O'Donnell|first1=Paul|date=February 20, 2013|website=[[CNBC]]|publisher=CNBC LLC.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117031837/http://www.cnbc.com/id/100475323|archive-date=November 17, 2015|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mic.com/articles/69539/these-7-schools-have-the-richest-alumni-is-yours-on-the-list|title=These 7 Schools Have the Richest Alumni \u2014 Is Yours On the List?|website=mic.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701085518/http://mic.com/articles/69539/these-7-schools-have-the-richest-alumni-is-yours-on-the-list|archive-date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/worlds-top-100-universities-for-producing-millionaires/2008749.article|title=World's top 100 universities for producing millionaires|website=Times Higher Education|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115105352/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/financial-times-executive-mba-ranking-2015-top-100|archive-date=January 15, 2017|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chasewithorn/2016/07/06/the-28-schools-that-mint-the-most-billionaire-alumni/|title=The 28 Schools That Mint The Most Billionaire Alumni|last=Peterson-Withorn|first=Chase|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bestcollegereviews.org/features/the-30-most-influential-colleges-and-universities-of-the-past-century/|title=The 30 Most Influential Colleges and Universities of the Past Century - Best College Reviews|website=www.bestcollegereviews.org|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Multiple [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhode Scholars]], [[Marshall Scholarship|Marshal Scholars]], [[Schwarzman Scholars]], and a [[Mitchell Scholarship|Mitchell Scholar]] are affiliated with the university, with NYU Abu Dhabi producing more Rhodes Scholars per student than any university in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyuad.nyu.edu/en/news/latest-news/honors-and-awards/2019/november-/nyuad-students-selected-as-2020-uae-rhodes-scholars.html|title=Two NYU Abu Dhabi students selected as 2020 UAE Rhodes Scholars|last=Dhabi|first=NYU Abu|website=New York University Abu Dhabi|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shanghai.nyu.edu/news/three-nyu-shanghai-seniors-receive-schwarzman-scholars-fellowship|title=Three NYU Shanghai Seniors Receive Schwarzman Scholars Fellowship|date=2019-12-04|website=shanghai.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marshallscholarship.org/the-scholars/scholar-profiles/rose-asaf|title=Rose Asaf - Marshall Scholarships|website=www.marshallscholarship.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyunews.com/news/2019/12/04/liberal-studies-rebecca-brett-named-george-j-mitchell-scholar/|title=Chess Led This Student to Become NYU\u2019s First Mitchell Scholar {{!}} Washington Square News|last=Mohammadi|first=Mina|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of New York University}}\n[[File:Albert Gallatin (by Gilbert Stuart).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Albert Gallatin]] (1761\u20131849) by [[Gilbert Stuart]]]]\n\n[[Albert Gallatin]], [[Secretary of Treasury]] under [[Thomas Jefferson]] and [[James Madison]], declared his intention to establish \"in this immense and fast-growing city ... a system of rational and practical education fitting and graciously opened to all.\"<ref name=\"About NYU\" /> A three-day-long \"literary and scientific convention\" held in [[New York City Hall|City Hall]] in 1830 and attended by over 100 delegates debated the terms of a plan for a new university. These New Yorkers believed the city needed a university designed for young men who would be admitted based upon merit rather than birthright or social class.\n\nOn April 18, 1831, the institution that would become NYU was established with the support of a group of prominent New York City residents from the city's [[merchant]]s, [[banker]]s, and [[trader (finance)|trader]]s.<ref name=\"NYU and the City\">{{cite book |last=Frusciano |first=Thomas |lastauthoramp=yes |last2=Pettit |first2=Marilyn |title=New York University and the City: An Illustrated History |location=New Brunswick, NJ |publisher=Rutgers University Press |year=1997 |isbn= }}</ref> Albert Gallatin was elected as its first president.<ref name=\"NYU in Retrospect\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/thenandnow/ |title=A Window Into the Past: NYU in Retrospect |last1=Friss |first1=Evan |last2= |first2= |website=NYU Archives |publisher=New York University |accessdate=August 30, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719014440/http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/thenandnow/ |archive-date=July 19, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> On April 21, 1831, the new institution received its [[charter]] and was incorporated as the University of the City of New York by the [[New York State Legislature]]; older documents often refer to it by that name. The university has been popularly known as New York University since its inception and was officially renamed New York University in 1896.<ref name=\"NYU in Retrospect\" /> In 1832, NYU held its first classes in rented rooms of four-story Clinton Hall, situated near [[New York City Hall|City Hall]].<ref name=\"NYU in Retrospect\" /> In 1835, the [[NYU School of Law|School of Law]], NYU's first professional school, was established. Although the impetus to found a new school was partly a reaction by [[evangelical]] [[Presbyterian]]s to what they perceived as the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalianism]] of [[Columbia College, Columbia University|Columbia College]],<ref name=gotham>{{cite gotham}} pp. 531\u2013532</ref> NYU was created [[non-denominational]], unlike many American colleges at the time.<ref name=\"NYU in Retrospect\" /> [[American Chemical Society]] was founded in 1876 at NYU.\n\n[[File:New York University Building in Washington Square, 1850.jpg|thumb|left|NYU Building in Washington Square, 1850]]\n[[File:Nyuuniheights.jpg|thumb|left|The University Heights campus, now home to [[Bronx Community College]]]]\nSoon after its founding it became one of the nation's largest universities, with an enrollment of 9,300 in 1917.<ref>{{cite enc-nyc}}, pp 848\u201349</ref> NYU had its [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] campus since its founding. The university purchased a campus at [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] in [[the Bronx]] because of overcrowding on the old campus. NYU also had a desire to follow New York City's development further uptown. NYU's move to the Bronx occurred in 1894, spearheaded by the efforts of Chancellor [[Henry Mitchell MacCracken]].<ref name=\"NYU in Retrospect\" /> The University Heights campus was far more spacious than its predecessor was. As a result, most of the university's operations along with the undergraduate [[NYU College of Arts and Science|College of Arts and Science]] and School of Engineering were housed there. NYU's administrative operations were moved to the new campus, but the graduate schools of the university remained at Washington Square.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/175/pages/heights.htm |title=175 Facts About NYU |publisher=NYU.edu |accessdate=December 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202090625/http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/175/pages/heights.htm |archive-date=February 2, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1914, Washington Square College was founded as the downtown undergraduate college of NYU. In 1935, NYU opened the \"Nassau College-Hofstra Memorial of New York University at Hempstead, Long Island.\" This extension would later become a fully independent [[Hofstra University]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hofstra.edu/alumni/support/devcc/devcc_growth.html | title = Capital Campaign | publisher = Hofstra University | accessdate = February 22, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081223092241/http://www.hofstra.edu/alumni/support/devcc/devcc_growth.html | archivedate = December 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1950, NYU was elected to the [[Association of American Universities]], a nonprofit organization of leading public and private research universities.<ref name=\"AAU members\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aau.edu/about/article.aspx?id=5476 |title=Member Institutions and Years of Admission |website=Association of American Universities |publisher=Association of American Universities |accessdate=August 30, 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69oUMM90E?url=http://www.aau.edu/about/article.aspx?id=5476 |archive-date=August 10, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"AAU about\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aau.edu/about/default.aspx?id=58 |title=About AAU |website=Association of American Universities |publisher=Association of American Universities |accessdate=August 30, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922040713/http://www.aau.edu/about/default.aspx?id=58 |archive-date=September 22, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1960s and early 1970s, financial crisis gripped the New York City government and the troubles spread to the city's institutions, including NYU.<ref name=\"nyuandvillage\">{{cite web | title = NYU and the Village: History | work =  | publisher = New York University Archives | url = http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/collections/exhibits/bobst/washsq/history/history.html | accessdate = July 17, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012185420/http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/collections/exhibits/bobst/washsq/history/history.html | archive-date = October 12, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> Feeling the pressures of imminent bankruptcy, NYU President [[James McNaughton Hester]] negotiated the sale of the University Heights campus to the [[City University of New York]], which occurred in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chronopoulos|first=Themis|title=Urban Decline and the Withdrawal of New York University from University Heights, The Bronx\". ''The Bronx County Historical Society Journal'' XLVI (Spring/Fall 2009): 4\u201324.|url=http://themis.slass.org/university-heights.html|accessdate=December 6, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031124152/http://themis.slass.org/university-heights.html|archivedate=October 31, 2014}}</ref> In 1973, the New York University School of Engineering and Science merged into [[Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn]],<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/05/education/brooklyn-s-polytech-a-storybook-success.html|title=Brooklyn'S Polytech, A Storybook Success|date=January 5, 1986|accessdate=November 22, 2015|first1=Cynthia|last1=Sanz|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117051744/http://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/05/education/brooklyn-s-polytech-a-storybook-success.html|archive-date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> which eventually merged back into NYU in 2014 forming the present [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]]. After the sale of the Bronx campus, University College merged with Washington Square College. In the 1980s, under the leadership of President [[John Brademas]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Laura Turegano|title=\"Fundraising Beyond U.S. Borders \u2013 NYU: A Success Story\"|website=Onphilanthropy.com|date=December 13, 2001|url=http://www.onphilanthropy.com/prof_inter/pi2001-12-13a.html|accessdate=October 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060105170859/http://www.onphilanthropy.com/prof_inter/pi2001-12-13a.html|archivedate=January 5, 2006}}</ref> NYU launched a billion-dollar campaign that was spent almost entirely on updating facilities.<ref>{{Cite news | first = Kenneth R. | last = Weiss | title = NYU Earns Respect | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = March 22, 2000 | url = http://www.nyu.edu/financial.aid/latimes2000-03-22.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = October 11, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060723180626/http://www.nyu.edu/financial.aid/latimes2000-03-22.pdf | archive-date = July 23, 2006 | url-status = live }}</ref> The campaign was set to complete in 15 years, but ended up being completed in 10.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE6DE1F3BF933A15750C0A963958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1 |title= Buying Excellence: How N.Y.U. Rebuilt Itself \u2013 A special report.; Decade and $1 Billion Put N.Y.U. With the Elite |author=Honan, William H. |author-link=William H. Honan |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 20, 1995 |accessdate=March 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, [[L. Jay Oliva]] was inaugurated the 14th president of the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/473|title=Higher Education Leaders From Around the World Meet at NYU to Discuss Financial Challenges and Fundraising|date=February 12, 1999|publisher=NYU Office of Public Affairs|accessdate=October 11, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060907102912/http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/473|archive-date=September 7, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> Following his inauguration, he moved to form the [[League of World Universities]], an international organization consisting of [[Rector (academia)|rectors]] and [[University president|president]]s from [[urban area|urban]] [[universities]] across six continents. The league and its 47 representatives gather every two years to discuss global issues in [[education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mndaily.com/articles/2002/10/02/33504|title=League of World Universities meets for forum|date=October 2, 2002|publisher=[[Minnesota Daily]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414192729/http://www.mndaily.com/articles/2002/10/02/33504|archivedate=April 14, 2008|accessdate=October 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 President [[John Sexton]] launched a $2.5 billion campaign for funds to be spent especially on faculty and financial aid resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/alumni/newsletter/0105/campaign.html|title=NYU Kicks Off $2.5 Billion Campaign|date=January 2005|work=|publisher=NYU Office for University Development and Alumni relations|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612185959/http://www.nyu.edu/alumni/newsletter/0105/campaign.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=June 12, 2007|accessdate=July 15, 2007}}</ref> Under Sextons leadership, NYU also began its radical transformation into a global university.\n\nIn 2009, the university responded to a series of ''New York Times'' interviews that showed a pattern of labor abuses in its fledgling [[New York University Abu Dhabi|Abu Dhabi]] location, creating a statement of labor values for Abu Dhabi campus workers. A 2014 follow-up article found that while some conditions had improved, contractors for the multibillion-endowment university were still frequently subjecting their workers to third-world labor conditions. The article documented that these conditions included confiscation of worker passports, forced overtime, recruitment fees and cockroach-filled dorms where workers had to sleep under beds. According to the article, workers who attempted to protest the NYU contractors' conditions were promptly arrested.<ref name=Kaminer>{{cite news|last=Kaminer|first=Ariel|title=Workers at N.Y.U.'s Abu Dhabi Site Faced Harsh Conditions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/nyregion/workers-at-nyus-abu-dhabi-site-face-harsh-conditions.html|accessdate=May 20, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519234118/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/nyregion/workers-at-nyus-abu-dhabi-site-face-harsh-conditions.html|archive-date=May 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports also claimed that those arrested by police were later abused at the police station. Many workers who were not local were then deported to their home countries.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/nyregion/workers-at-nyus-abu-dhabi-site-face-harsh-conditions.html?_r=2 | work=The New York Times | first1=Ariel | last1=Kaminer | first2=Sean | last2=O'Driscoll | title=Workers at N.Y.U.'s Abu Dhabi Site Faced Harsh Conditions | date=May 18, 2014 | access-date=February 11, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224174811/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/nyregion/workers-at-nyus-abu-dhabi-site-face-harsh-conditions.html?_r=2 | archive-date=February 24, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> The university quickly responded to the reports with an apology to the workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/20/nyregion/nyu-apologizes-to-any-workers-mistreated-on-its-abu-dhabi-campus.html|title=N.Y.U. Apologizes to Any Workers Mistreated on Its Abu Dhabi Campus|date=May 20, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=February 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622164229/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/20/nyregion/nyu-apologizes-to-any-workers-mistreated-on-its-abu-dhabi-campus.html|archive-date=June 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, NYU compensated thousands of migrant workers on its Abu Dhabi complex.<ref>{{cite news |author=David Batty |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2015/apr/24/nyu-compensate-thousands-migrant-workers-abu-dhabi-complex-nardello-report |title=NYU set to compensate thousands of migrant workers on Abu Dhabi complex &#124; Global development |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=February 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223013254/http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2015/apr/24/nyu-compensate-thousands-migrant-workers-abu-dhabi-complex-nardello-report |archive-date=February 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to 2018, NYU experienced a 114% increase in applications to its university system, increasing from around 35,000 applicants to nearly 85,000 in 2019. This has also caused the acceptance rate to drop significantly, with a record-low acceptance rate of 16% in 2019.<ref name=\"class of 2023\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2019/march/Class_of_2023_Admits.html|title=NYU Admits Most Diverse Class in Its History|last=Beckman|first=John|date=March 28, 2019|website=nyu.edu|access-date=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404032700/https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2019/march/Class_of_2023_Admits.html|archive-date=April 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In parallel to NYU's expansion in the early 1900s, the university similarly expanded vigorously in the early 2000s, becoming the largest private university in the United States with a combined undergraduate/graduate enrollment of over 59,000 students as of 2018.\n\nIn August 2018, the [[New York University School of Medicine]] announced it would be offering full-tuition scholarships to all current and future students in its MD program regardless of need or merit, making it the only top-10 medical school in the United States to do so.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/nyregion/nyu-free-tuition-medical-school.html|title=Surprise Gift: Free Tuition for All N.Y.U. Medical Students|access-date=September 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831152509/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/16/nyregion/nyu-free-tuition-medical-school.html|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===University logo===\nThe university logo, the upheld [[torch]], is derived from the [[Statue of Liberty]], signifying NYU's service to New York City. The torch is depicted on both the NYU seal and the more abstract NYU logo, designed in 1965 by renowned graphic designer [[Tom Geismar]] of the branding and design firm [[Chermayeff & Geismar]]. There are at least two versions of the possible origin of the university color, [[Violet (color)|violet]]. Some believe that it may have been chosen because [[Violet (plant)|violets]] are said to have grown abundantly in Washington Square and around the buttresses of the Old University Building. Others argue that the color may have been adopted because the violet was the flower associated with [[Athens]], the center of learning in [[ancient Greece]].\n\n===Cultural setting===\n[[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] and [[Greenwich Village]] have been hubs of [[cultural learning|cultural life]] in New York City since the early 19th century. Much of this culture has intersected with NYU at various points in its history. [[Artist]]s of the [[Hudson River School]], the United States' first prominent school of painters, settled around Washington Square. [[Samuel F.B. Morse]], a noted artist who also pioneered the telegraph and created the Morse Code, served as the first chair of Painting and Sculpture. He and [[Daniel Huntington (artist)|Daniel Huntington]] were early tenants of the Old University Building in the mid-19th century. (The university rented out studio space and residential apartments within the \"academic\" building.) As a result, they had notable interaction with the cultural and academic life of the university.<ref name=\"nyuandvillage\"/>\n\nIn the 1870s, sculptors [[Augustus Saint-Gaudens]] and [[Daniel Chester French]] lived and worked near the Square. By the 1920s, [[Washington Square Park]] was nationally recognized as a focal point for artistic and moral rebellion. As such, the Washington Square campus became more diverse and bustled with urban energy, contributing to academic change at NYU.<ref name=\"nyuandvillage\"/> Famed residents of this time include [[Eugene O'Neill]], [[John French Sloan|John Sloan]], and [[Maurice Prendergast]]. In the 1930s, the abstract expressionists [[Jackson Pollock]] and [[Willem de Kooning]], and the realists [[Edward Hopper]] and [[Thomas Hart Benton (painter)|Thomas Hart Benton]] had studios around Washington Square. In the 1960s the area became one of the centers of the beat and folk generation, when [[Allen Ginsberg]] and [[Bob Dylan]] settled there. This led to tension with the university, which at the time was in the midst of an aggressive facilities expansion phase.<ref name=\"nyuandvillage\"/> In 1975, the university opened The [[Grey Art Gallery]] at 100 Washington Square East, housing the NYU art collection and featuring museum quality exhibitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/collection/collection.html|title=Home - Grey Gallery|work=Grey Gallery|access-date=March 5, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225120726/http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/collection/collection.html|archive-date=December 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/|title=Home - Grey Gallery|work=Grey Gallery|access-date=March 5, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110318163541/http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/|archive-date=March 18, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Budget and fundraising===\nNYU has successfully completed a seven-year, $2.5 billion campaign, surpassing expectations by raising more than $3 billion over the seven-year period.<ref>{{cite web | last = Masterson | first = Kathryn | year = 2008 | url = http://chronicle.com/news/article/5430/nyu-sets-record-with-31-billion-campaign | title = NYU Sets Record With $3.1-Billion Campaign | accessdate = November 1, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090211081654/http://chronicle.com/news/article/5430/nyu-sets-record-with-31-billion-campaign | archive-date = February 11, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> Started in 2001, this campaign was the university's largest in its history, in which they planned to \"raise $1 million per day for scholarships and financial aid, faculty building, new academic initiatives, and enhancing NYU's physical facilities.\"<ref name=\"campaignnews\">{{Cite book | last = Beckman | first = John | title = New York University Kick Off $2.5 Billion Fundraising Campaign | publisher = NYU Office Public Affairs | date = April 28, 2004 | url = http://www.nyu.edu/publicaffairs/newsreleases/b_nyu_campaign_09282004.shtml | accessdate = September 4, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070812191704/http://www.nyu.edu/publicaffairs/newsreleases/b_nyu_campaign_09282004.shtml | archive-date = August 12, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> The campaign included a $50 million gift from the Tisch family (after which one building and the [[Tisch School of the Arts|art school]] are named) and a $60 million gift from six [[trustee]]s called \"The Partners Fund,\" aimed at hiring new faculty.<ref name=\"campaignnews\"/><ref name=\"campaign\">{{cite web| title = The Campaign for NYU | publisher = NYU Office for University Development & Alumni Relations | url = http://campaign.nyu.edu/ | accessdate = September 4, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070822075608/http://campaign.nyu.edu/ |archivedate = August 22, 2007}}</ref> On October 15, 2007 the university announced that the Silver family donated $50 million to the [[NYU School of Social Work|School of Social Work]], which will be renamed as a result.<ref>{{Cite book | title = NYU Alumni Constance & Martin Silver Donate $50 Million to University's School of Social Work | publisher = NYU Office Public Affairs | date = October 15, 2007 | url = http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/1790 | accessdate = October 17, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071016134618/http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/1790 | archive-date = October 16, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> This is the largest donation ever to a school of social work in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book | first = Scott | last = Jaschik | title = Quick Takes | publisher = [[Inside Higher Ed]] | date = October 17, 2007 | url = http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/10/17/qt | accessdate = October 17, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071019043103/http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/10/17/qt | archive-date = October 19, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe 2007\u20132008 academic year was the most successful fundraising year to date for NYU, with the school raising $698 million in only the first 11 months of the year, representing a 70% increase in donations from the prior year.<ref>{{cite web| last = Souccar | first = Miriam | year = 2008 | url = http://www.crainsnewyork.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080801/FREE/659182051/1046/toc | title = Local universities report banner fundraising years | accessdate = August 2, 2008}}</ref> The university also recently announced plans for NYU's Call to Action, a new initiative to ask alumni and donors to support financial aid for students at NYU.<ref>{{cite web|last=Platt |first=Eric |year=2008 |url=http://nyunews.com/news/university/over_seven_years%252C_nyu_rakes_in_3_billion |title=Over seven years, NYU rakes in $3 billion |accessdate=September 9, 2008 |archivedate=January 13, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113040435/http://nyunews.com/news/university/over_seven_years%2C_nyu_rakes_in_3_billion |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nThe university has announced a 25-year strategic development plan, scheduled to coincide with its [[wikt:bicentennial|bicentennial]] in 2031. Included in the \"NYU 200\" plans are increasing resident and academic space, hiring additional faculty, and involving the New York City community in a transparent planning process. Additionally, NYU hopes to make their buildings more environmentally friendly, which will be facilitated by an evaluation of all campus spaces.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Portlock | first = Sarah | title = NYU unveils 25-year plan | newspaper = [[Washington Square News]] | date = April 24, 2007 | url = http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2007/04/24/News/Nyu-Unveils.25Year.Plan-2876454.shtml | accessdate = September 4, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070822173414/http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2007/04/24/News/Nyu-Unveils.25Year.Plan-2876454.shtml |archivedate = August 22, 2007}}</ref> As a part of this plan, NYU purchased 118 million [[kilowatt-hours]] of [[wind power]] during the 2006\u20132007 academic year \u2013 the largest purchase of wind power by any university in the country and any institution in New York City.<ref name=\"GreenBiz.com\"/> For 2007, the university expanded its purchase of wind power to 132 million kilowatt-hours.<ref name=\"NYU buys more wind power credit\"/> As a result, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] ranked NYU as one of the greenest colleges in the country in its annual College & University Green Power Challenge.<ref name=\"NYU Office of Public Affairs\"/>\n\nNYU consistently ranks as one of the top fundraising institutions in the country, raising $506.4 million in 2015 and $648 million in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/office-of-the-provost/provostial-communications/the-2017-2018-budget.html|title=The 2017-2018 Budget|last=Fleming|first=Katherine|date=May 15, 2017|website=nyu.edu|access-date=July 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723003553/https://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/office-of-the-provost/provostial-communications/the-2017-2018-budget.html|archive-date=July 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> NYU is also the 19th wealthiest university in America with $5.3 billion in cash and investments in fiscal year 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-u-s-universities-the-rich-get-richer-faster-1429156904|title=For U.S. Universities, the Rich Get Richer Faster|author=Melissa Korn|date=April 16, 2015|work=WSJ|access-date=March 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320150550/https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-u-s-universities-the-rich-get-richer-faster-1429156904/|archive-date=March 20, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Main buildingNYU.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Silver Center]] c. 1900]]\n{{Main|Campus of New York University}}\n\nNYU's [[New York City]] campus includes more than 171 buildings spread between [[Manhattan]] and [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observer.com/2006/05/nyu-columbia-make-a-mint-on-real-estate/|title=NYU Columbia Make A Mint on Real Estate|website=observer.com|publisher=Observer Media|accessdate=October 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024091705/http://observer.com/2006/05/nyu-columbia-make-a-mint-on-real-estate/|archive-date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commercialobserver.com/2018/07/nyu-martin-dorph-real-estate-holdings/|title=NYU Martin Dorph Talks University's Real Estate Holdings|date=July 24, 2018|website=Commercialobserver.com|accessdate=September 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825102221/https://commercialobserver.com/2018/07/nyu-martin-dorph-real-estate-holdings/|archive-date=August 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of the school's buildings in Manhattan are located across a roughly {{convert|230|acre|m2|adj=on}} area bounded by [[Houston Street]] to the south, [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] to the east, [[14th Street (Manhattan)|14th Street]] to the north, and [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|Sixth Avenue]] (Avenue of the Americas) to the west. The core of NYU consists of buildings that surround [[Washington Square Park]].<ref name=\"Campus Map\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/footer/map.html |title=Campus Map |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015065022/http://www.nyu.edu/footer/map.html |archive-date=October 15, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/learn-at-nyu/a-global-network/new-york-campus.html |title=New York Campus |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200757/http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/learn-at-nyu/a-global-network/new-york-campus.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/learn-at-nyu/a-global-network.html |title=NYU's Global Network |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200848/http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/learn-at-nyu/a-global-network.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition to its New York campus, NYU has 49 additional buildings overseas located throughout two 'portal' campuses and 12 Global Academic Centers.\n\nWith approximately 12,000 undergraduate and graduate residents,<ref name=\"On Campus Living\" /> NYU had the seventh-largest university housing system in the U.S. {{as of|2007|lc=y}}, and one of the largest among private schools.<ref name=\"housingranking\"/>\n\n===Washington Square campus===\n[[File:Central Park Nueva York017.jpg|thumb|left|[[Washington Square Park]], with its gateway [[Washington Square Arch|arch]], is surrounded largely by NYU buildings and plays an integral role in the University's campus life.]]\n\nSince the late 1970s, the central part of NYU has been its Washington Square campus in the heart of [[Greenwich Village]]. The [[Washington Square Arch]] is an unofficial symbol of NYU. Until 2007, NYU had held its commencement ceremonies in Washington Square Park, but moved the ceremonies to [[Yankee Stadium]] in 2008 because of renovations to Washington Square.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement ceremony |publisher=NYU |url=http://www.nyu.edu/commencement/ceremony.html |accessdate=April 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411032533/http://www.nyu.edu/commencement/ceremony.html |archive-date=April 11, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, NYU became a \"two square\" university by building a second community around [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]], in close proximity to Washington Square. NYU's Union Square community primarily consists of the priority residence halls of Carlyle Court, [[Palladium (New York City)|Palladium]] Residence Hall, Alumni Hall, Coral Tower, Thirteenth Street Hall, University Hall, Third North Residence Hall, and Founders Hall.<ref name=\"Campus Map\" />\n\nNYU operates theaters and performance facilities that are often used by the university's [[music conservatory]] and [[Tisch School of the Arts]]. External productions are also occasionally held in NYU's facilities. The largest performance accommodations at NYU are the [[Skirball Center for Performing Arts]] (850 seats) at 566 LaGuardia Place, just south of Washington Square South, and the Eisner-Lubin Auditorium (560 seats) in the Kimmel Center. Recently, the Skirball Center hosted important speeches on foreign policy by [[John Kerry]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Speech at New York University | publisher = GlobalSecurity.org | date = April 20, 2004 | url = http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2004/09/iraq-040920-kerry01.htm | accessdate = July 15, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711231213/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2004/09/iraq-040920-kerry01.htm | archive-date = July 11, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> and [[Al Gore]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Former Vice President Al Gore Remarks to MoveOn.org | publisher = MoveOn.org | date = August 7, 2003 | url = http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html | accessdate = July 15, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070715151552/http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html | archivedate = July 15, 2007 }}</ref> The Skirball Center is the largest performing arts facility south of [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]].<ref>{{cite web| title = The Skirball Center for the Performing Arts | publisher = NYU Office for University Development and Alumni Relations | url = http://www.nyu.edu/kimmel/perf_arts.shtml | accessdate = July 15, 2007 |archivedate=February 20, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020220041238/http://www.nyu.edu/kimmel/perf_arts.shtml }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Helen and Martin Kimmel Center for University Life, NYU | publisher = Kevin Roche John Dinkeloo and Associates LLC \u2013 Architects | url = http://www.krjda.com/text/projectDetail.cfm?id=100 | accessdate = July 15, 2007 |archivedate=February 22, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050222230807/http://www.krjda.com/text/projectDetail.cfm?id=100 }}</ref>\n\n==== Gould Plaza ====\n[[Gould Plaza]], located between Washington Square East and [[Mercer Street (Manhattan)|Mercer Street]] on West [[4th Street (Manhattan)|4th Street]], is surrounded by the buildings for some departments of the NYU College of Arts and Science, Stern School of Business, and Courant Institute of Mathematics. Other NYU buildings nearby the plaza includes NYU\u2019s [[Student health|Student Health]] Center, NYU's [[University and college admission|admissions]] center, [[New York University residence halls|Goddard Hall]], Warren Weaver Hall, Frederick Loewe Theatre, [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library|NYU's Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], Kimmel Center for University Life, and NYU Steinhart's main building, as well as unrelated religious institutions such as [[Judson Memorial Church]], the [[Mosque|Islamic Center]] at NYU, and [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion|Hebrew Union College - Jewish Institute of Religion]]. Because of its high student traffic during the academic year, Gould Plaza has become a popular meeting spot for NYU students and a performance area for [[Street performance|street musicians and buskers]]. \n\n====Bobst Library====\n{{Main|Elmer Holmes Bobst Library|New York University Library}}\n[[File:NYU's Bobst library-2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A view of the interior of Bobst]]\n\nThe Elmer Holmes Bobst Library, built between 1967 and 1972, is the largest library at NYU and one of the largest academic libraries in the United States. Designed by [[Philip Johnson]] and [[Richard Foster (architect)|Richard Foster]], the 12-story, {{convert|425000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} structure sits on the southern edge of Washington Square Park (at 70 Washington Square South) and is the flagship of an eight-library, 4.5 million-volume system. Bobst Library offers one Multidisciplinary Reference Center, a Research Commons, {{Convert|28|miles}} of open-stacks shelving, and approximately 2,000 seats for student study. The library is visited by more than 6,800 users each day, and circulates more than one million books annually.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the NYU Libraries | work =  | publisher = NYU Libraries | date = June 2007 | url = http://library.nyu.edu/about/about.html | accessdate = July 15, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012185034/http://library.nyu.edu/about/about.html | archivedate = October 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBobst's Avery Fisher Center for Music and Media is one of the world's largest academic media centers, where students and researchers use more than 95,000 audio and video recordings per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.nyu.edu/afc/ |title=The Avery Fisher Center for Music and Media |website=New York University Libraries |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200800/http://library.nyu.edu/afc/ |archivedate=November 2, 2013  }}</ref> The Digital Studio offers a constantly evolving, leading-edge resource for faculty and student projects and promotes and supports access to digital resources for teaching, learning, research and arts events.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyu.libguides.com/digitalstudio |title=Digital Studio |website=New York University Libraries |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102023315/http://nyu.libguides.com/digitalstudio |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBobst Library is also home to many special collections. The [[Fales Library|Fales Collection]] houses collections of English and American fiction in the United States, the unique Downtown Collection, documenting the New York literary avante-garde arts scene from the 1970s to the present, and the Food and Cookery Collection, which documents American food history with a focus on New York City. Bobst Library also houses the Tamiment Library, which holds collections in labor history, socialism, anarchism, communism, and American radicalism for scholarly research. Tamiment includes the Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, the Archives of Irish America, the Center for the Cold War and the U.S., and the Frederic Ewen Academic Freedom Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.nyu.edu/collections/archives.html |title=Special Collections and Archives |website=New York University Libraries |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029083700/http://library.nyu.edu/collections/archives.html |archivedate=October 29, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nBobst Library made headlines in the early 2000s when [[Bobst Boy|Steven Stanzak]], who is also known as \"Bobst Boy\", gained a following for living in Bobst Library after he was unable to pay for board at the university and began to write about his life on a self published blog.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/3665885.stm|title=Broke student 'slept in library'|date=2004-04-28|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB}}</ref> The story was reported by ''[[Washington Square News]]'' before becoming an overnight national sensation, which helped Stanzak receive financial assistance from NYU until graduation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/bobst-boy-life-after-the-stacks-4900d117cab1|title=Bobst Boy: Life After The Stacks|last=Local|first=N. Y. U.|date=2019-09-23|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> \n\n===Brooklyn campus===\n[[File:NYU Poly - Brooklyn, NY - DSC07632.JPG|thumb|left|Bern Dibner Library of Science and Technology on the Brooklyn campus]]\nNYU's Brooklyn campus is located at [[MetroTech Center]], an urban academic-industrial [[research park]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> It sits on top of the [[Jay Street\u2013MetroTech station]], is only a few blocks from the Brooklyn Bridge, and is connected to NYU's Manhattan campus via the NYU Shuttle Bus System.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/travel-and-transportation/university-transportation/routes-and-schedules/route-a.html|title=Route A|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=October 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906031920/http://www.nyu.edu/life/travel-and-transportation/university-transportation/routes-and-schedules/route-a.html|archive-date=September 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/travel-and-transportation/university-transportation/passenger-information.html|title=Passenger Information|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=October 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907004823/http://www.nyu.edu/life/travel-and-transportation/university-transportation/passenger-information.html|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It houses the [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|School of Engineering]], the [[Center for Urban Science and Progress]] and also several of [[Tisch School of the Arts]]<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animationcareerreview.com/articles/top-50-game-design-schools-and-colleges-us-%E2%80%93-2015|title=Top 50 Game Design Schools and Colleges in the US \u2013 2015|work=animationcareerreview.com|access-date=August 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901064011/http://www.animationcareerreview.com/articles/top-50-game-design-schools-and-colleges-us-%E2%80%93-2015|archive-date=September 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]]'s degree programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magnet.nyu.edu/|title=MAGNET - NYU Media and Games Network|work=nyu.edu|access-date=August 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150812020451/http://magnet.nyu.edu/|archive-date=August 12, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The Brooklyn campus also houses NYU's Game Center Open Library, which is the largest collection of games held by any university in the world.<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\"/> In 2014, [[NYU Langone Medical Center]] acquired a {{Convert|125000|sqft}} healthcare facility in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Mary|title=NYU Langone to take over LICH emergency department in Brooklyn on Friday|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|accessdate=April 4, 2016|date=October 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404102307/http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday|archive-date=April 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Quickly following this announcement, NYU announced in 2017 that it would invest over $500 million in the coming years to renovate and expand its Brooklyn campus, including [[370 Jay Street]], which opened in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ny.curbed.com/2017/1/26/14397270/nyus-500m-downtown-brooklyn-expansion-will-open-this-summer|title=NYU\u2019s $500M Downtown Brooklyn expansion will open this summer|work=Curbed NY|access-date=November 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171114093646/https://ny.curbed.com/2017/1/26/14397270/nyus-500m-downtown-brooklyn-expansion-will-open-this-summer|archive-date=November 14, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Other NYC facilities===\n[[File:11 W42 calendar jeh.JPG|thumb|upright|11 West 42nd Street]]\n[[File:NYU Maison francaise.gif|thumb|left|[[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]]]]\n\nThe [[New York University School of Medicine]] is situated near the East River waterfront at 550 First Avenue between East [[30th Street (Manhattan)|30th]] and [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th]] Streets. The campus hosts the medical school, Tisch Hospital, and the [[Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://school.med.nyu.edu/contact-us |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704070730/http://school.med.nyu.edu/contact-us |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 4, 2011 |title=Contact Us |website=NYU School of Medicine |publisher=NYU Langone Medical Center |accessdate=October 31, 2013 }}</ref> Other NYU Centers across the city include NYU Hospital for Joint Diseases and the [[Bellevue Hospital Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hjd.med.nyu.edu/about-us |title=About Us |website=Hospital for Joint Diseases |publisher=NYU Langone Medical Center |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200723/http://hjd.med.nyu.edu/about-us |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.nyu.edu/patients-visitors/our-hospitals/bellevue-hospital-center |title=Bellevue Hospital Center |website=NYU Langone Medical Center |publisher=NYU Langone Medical Center |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200844/http://www.med.nyu.edu/patients-visitors/our-hospitals/bellevue-hospital-center |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> NYU's Silver School of Social Work (formerly Ehrenkranz School of Social Work) manages branch campus programs in Westchester County at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] and in [[Rockland County]] at [[St. Thomas Aquinas College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://socialwork.nyu.edu/contact.html |title=Contact |website=NYU Silver School of Social Work |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200848/http://socialwork.nyu.edu/contact.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn [[Sterling Forest, New York|Sterling Forest]], near [[Tuxedo, New York|Tuxedo]], NYU has a research facility that contains institutes, in particular the Nelson Institute of Environmental Medicine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medicine.med.nyu.edu/pulmonary/research/centers/nelson-institute-environmental-medicine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130401065120/http://medicine.med.nyu.edu/pulmonary/research/centers/nelson-institute-environmental-medicine |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 1, 2013 |title=Nelson Institute of Environmental Medicine |website=Pulmonary, Critical Care, & Sleep Medicine \u2013 Department of Medicine |publisher=NYU Langone Medical Center |accessdate=October 31, 2013 }}</ref> The Midtown Center at 11 West 42nd Street is home to the NYU Schack Institute of Real Estate. The [[Woolworth Building]] in the financial district is home to NYU's professional studies and education programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scps.nyu.edu/visit-us.html |title=Visit Us |website=NYU School of Professional Studies |publisher=New York University School of Professional Studies |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020145928/http://www.scps.nyu.edu/visit-us.html |archive-date=October 20, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNYU has two units located on the [[Upper East Side]]. The [[Institute for the Study of the Ancient World]], a discrete entity within NYU, independent of any other school or department of the university, is located on East 84th Street,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://isaw.nyu.edu/ |title=Institute for the Study of the Ancient World |website=Institute for the Study of the Ancient World |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028150530/http://isaw.nyu.edu/ |archive-date=October 28, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> while the [[New York University Institute of Fine Arts]], a graduate school of art history and fine arts, is located at the James B. Duke Building at 1 East 78th Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/fineart/contact.htm |title=Contact the Institute |website=NYU Institute of Fine Arts |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200800/http://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/fineart/contact.htm |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNYU has international houses on its Manhattan campus, including the Deutsches Haus, [[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]], [[Casa Italiana Zerilli Marim\u00f2]], the Glucksman Ireland House, the [[King Juan Carlos I of Spain]] Center, the [[Hagop Kevorkian]] Center, an Africa House and a China House.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://as.nyu.edu/page/research#ih |title=Research Centers, Institutes, and International Houses |website=NYU Arts & Science |publisher=New York University, Arts and Science |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030054058/http://as.nyu.edu/page/research#ih |archivedate=October 30, 2013  }}</ref>\n\n=== Global campuses and sites ===\nTisch School of the Arts, Asia was NYU's first branch campus abroad. The result of a partnership between [[Tisch School of the Arts]] and the Singapore Government, it offered Master of Fine Arts degrees in animation and digital arts, dramatic writing, film and international media producing. The campus opened in fall 2007 with the intention to enroll approximately 250 students.<ref>\n{{cite news | url = http://www.edb.gov.sg/edb/sg/en_uk/index/news/articles/nyu_s_tisch_school.html | title = NYU's Tisch School Of The Arts opens its first campus in Singapore | accessdate = August 22, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120223143728/http://www.edb.gov.sg/edb/sg/en_uk/index/news/articles/nyu_s_tisch_school.html | archivedate = February 23, 2012 }}</ref> Anticipated enrolment figures were not achieved, financial irregularities were alleged and President Pari Sara Shirazi was dismissed from her post by NYU in November 2011.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.edvantage.com.sg/edvantage/news/schoolnews/970962/Tisch_asia_in_a_flux_following_president_s_removal.html | title = Tisch Asia in a flux following president's removal | accessdate = November 9, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121019103847/http://www.edvantage.com.sg/edvantage/news/schoolnews/970962/Tisch_asia_in_a_flux_following_president_s_removal.html | archive-date = October 19, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> She subsequently announced her intention to commence legal proceedings against NYU alleging wrongful termination and defamation.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.asiaone.com/A1Business/General%2BNews/Story/A1Story20121009-376501.html | title = Ex-Tisch Asia president takes NYU to court | accessdate = November 9, 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121119045909/http://www.asiaone.com/A1Business/General%2BNews/Story/A1Story20121009-376501.html | archivedate = November 19, 2012 }}</ref> In a letter to the Tisch Asia community dated November 8, 2012, Dean Mary Schmidt Campbell announced that the campus would close after 2014 with recruitment and admission of new students suspended with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.tischasia.nyu.edu.sg/attach/209829.html?type=support&primitive=0 | title = 'The Future Of Tisch Asia'' (Memo from Office of the Dean to Tisch Asia Community) | accessdate = November 9, 2012 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2016, three former students of the now defunct Tisch Asia sued NYU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2016/09/20/nyu-students-claim-defunct-tisch-asia-was-a-rip-off-in-suit/|title=NYU students claim defunct Tisch Asia was a rip-off in suit|first=Lia|last=Eustachewich|date=September 20, 2016|website=Nypost.com|accessdate=September 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923200041/http://nypost.com/2016/09/20/nyu-students-claim-defunct-tisch-asia-was-a-rip-off-in-suit/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ex-students-call-nyu-singapore-art-school-educational-scam-article-1.2798769|title=Ex-students call NYU's Singapore art school an 'educational scam'|website=Nydailynews.com|accessdate=September 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923015023/http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ex-students-call-nyu-singapore-art-school-educational-scam-article-1.2798769|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNYU has a host of foreign facilities used for [[study abroad|study away]] programs, referred to as Global Academic Centers. {{as of|2012}}, NYU operates 12 academic sites in Africa, Asia and the Middle East, Australia, Europe, North America, and South America, including undergraduate academic-year and summer study abroad programs in [[Accra]], [[Berlin]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[NYU Florence|Florence]], [[NYU London|London]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Madrid]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], [[Prague]], [[Sydney]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"NYU overseas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2012/09/24/nyu-opens-academic-center-in-washington-dc.html|title=NYU Opens Academic Center In Washington, DC|year=2012|publisher=NYU|accessdate=October 12, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006091757/http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2012/09/24/nyu-opens-academic-center-in-washington-dc.html|archive-date=October 6, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/global/global-academic-centers1.html|title=Global Academic Centers|publisher=New York University|accessdate=February 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201235310/http://www.nyu.edu/global/global-academic-centers1.html|archive-date=February 1, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the most noteworthy is the {{convert|57|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus of NYU Florence [[Villa LaPietra]] in Italy, bequeathed by the late Sir [[Harold Acton]] to NYU in 1994, that at the time was the largest donation to a university in history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/16/01/Stories/LaPietra.html|title=NYU marks years of successful restoration at La Pietra|date=September 5, 2002|newspaper=NYU Today|accessdate=July 16, 2007|issue=1|volume=16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808213200/http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/16/01/Stories/LaPietra.html|archive-date=August 8, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn spring 2014, NYU opened a new campus in [[Paris]], in the student area of the [[Quartier Latin]], where NYU Law set up an EU Regulatory Policy Clinic taught by [[Alberto Alemanno]] and [[Vincent Chauvet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letudiant.fr/educpros/actualite/a-paris-la-new-york-university-demenage-et-lance-une-clinique-du-droit.html|title=\u00c0 Paris, la New York University d\u00e9m\u00e9nage et lance une clinique du droit \u2013 Educpros|date=October 28, 2013|publisher=Letudiant.fr|accessdate=August 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017114945/http://www.letudiant.fr/educpros/actualite/a-paris-la-new-york-university-demenage-et-lance-une-clinique-du-droit.html|archive-date=October 17, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Abu Dhabi campus ====\nIn fall 2010, [[NYU Abu Dhabi]] (NYUAD) opened as the university's first overseas \"Portal Campus\" with an inaugural class of 150 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyuad.nyu.edu/|title=NYU Abu Dhabi University & College in UAE, New York University|publisher=New York University Abu Dhabi|accessdate=February 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202065817/http://nyuad.nyu.edu/|archive-date=February 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Unlike NYU's other study abroad centers, NYUAD functions as a separate liberal arts college within a university, offering complete degree programs to students admitted directly to NYUAD. NYUAD recruits students from all over the world and describes itself as the \"World's Honor College.\" The main campus for NYUAD is under construction on Saadiyat Island and is scheduled to open in 2014. Until then the school operates from a campus located in downtown Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/21/education/21nyu.html|title=N.Y.U. Abu Dhabi Scours Globe for Its First Students|last=Foderaro|first=Lisa W.|date=June 20, 2010|work=New York Times|accessdate=February 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522120348/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/21/education/21nyu.html|archive-date=May 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The campus construction and operational costs are entirely funded by the Abu Dhabi government.<ref name=\"abu dhabi\">{{cite web|url=http://nyunews.com/news/2010/09/13/13abudhabi/|title=NYU Abu Dhabi: the story from concept to classroom|last=Timm|first=Jane|date=September 13, 2010|publisher=nyunews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917064857/http://nyunews.com/news/2010/09/13/13abudhabi/|archivedate=September 17, 2010|accessdate=November 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Shanghai campus ====\nIn 2011, NYU announced plans to open another portal campus, [[New York University Shanghai]], for the fall semester of 2013. It was set to have about 3,000 undergraduate students, the majority of whom would be [[Chinese people|Chinese]]. It was approved by the [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China]] in January 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyulocal.com/on-campus/2011/01/21/chinas-education-ministry-approves-nyu-portal-campus-in-shanghai/|title=China's Education Ministry Approves NYU Portal Campus in Shanghai|date=January 21, 2011|publisher=NYU Local|accessdate=April 21, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605034108/http://nyulocal.com/on-campus/2011/01/21/chinas-education-ministry-approves-nyu-portal-campus-in-shanghai/|archive-date=June 5, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> NYU's local partner will be [[East China Normal University]] (ECNU). ECNU's president [[Yu Lizhong]] will be the chancellor and play a major role in government relations while [[Jeffrey S. Lehman]], former president of [[Cornell]] amongst other positions, will serve as vice chancellor and have \"free rein in academic affairs.\"<ref>Hennock, Mary, [http://chronicle.com/article/New-Leader-of-NYU-Shanghai-Has/131730/ \"New Leader of NYU Shanghai Has Built Other Bridges to China\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509061707/http://chronicle.com/article/New-Leader-of-NYU-Shanghai-Has/131730 |date=May 9, 2012 }}, ''[[Chronicle of Higher Education]]'', April 29, 2012. Retrieved April 30, 2012.</ref>\n\n===Residence halls===\n{{Main|New York University residence halls}}\n[[File:Washington Square Village Jul 2007.jpg|thumb|left|[[Washington Square Village]], home to NYU faculty and graduate students]]\n\nNYU houses approximately 12,000 undergraduate and graduate residents,<ref name=\"On Campus Living\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu/on-campus-living.html |title=On Campus Living |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102201020/http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu/on-campus-living.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and had the seventh-largest university housing system in the U.S. {{as of|2007|lc=y}}, and one of the largest among private schools.<ref name=\"housingranking\">{{cite web| title = Top Ten Residence Hall Systems | publisher = [[University of Michigan]] Housing | url = http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html | accessdate = July 16, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070305034155/http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html |archivedate = March 5, 2007}}</ref> NYU's undergraduate housing system consists of more than 20 residence halls and is governed by the [[Residence hall association|Inter-Residence Hall Council]] (IRHC), an umbrella student council organization.<ref name=\"On Campus Living\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyuirhc.org/what-is-irhc/mission-statement/|title=Mission Statement|website=Inter-Residence Hall Council|publisher=Inter-Residence Hall Council|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102230701/http://nyuirhc.org/what-is-irhc/mission-statement/|archivedate=November 2, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUniquely, many of NYU's residence halls are converted [[apartment]] complexes or old hotels. In general, NYU residence halls receive favorable ratings, and some are opulent. Many rooms are spacious and contain amenities considered rare for individual college residence hall rooms, such as kitchens, lavatories, living rooms and common areas.<ref>{{Cite book| last = Turley | first = Meredith | title = New York University: Off the Record | publisher = [[College Prowler]] | date = July 1, 2006 | isbn = 978-1-4274-0102-1 | page = 161}}</ref> The university operates its own transit system to transport its students by [[bus]] to its campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/public.safety/transportation/routes.html |title=Routes and Schedules |website=Department of Public Safety |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200712/http://www.nyu.edu/public.safety/transportation/routes.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> A few of the Residence Halls are considered to be amongst the nicest in the nation{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}, being furnished with granite counter-tops, stainless-steel appliances, in-hall gyms, wood flooring, marble bathroom fixtures, large floor lounges, floor to ceiling windows and extensive views of lower and midtown Manhattan.\n\nUndergraduate students are guaranteed housing during their enrollment at NYU and are split into two categories, FYRE (First-Year Residential Experience) and TRUE (The Residential Upperclassmen Experience). Most FYRE halls are located near the Washington Square area. While nearly all TRUE halls are located near the [[Union Square (New York City)|Union Square]] area, two former residence halls were located in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] and one is still in use in [[Chinatown, Manhattan|Chinatown]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu.html |title=Living at NYU |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012034407/http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu.html |archive-date=October 12, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu/on-campus-living/explore-the-residencehalls.html |title=Explore the Residence Halls |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102201018/http://www.nyu.edu/life/living-at-nyu/on-campus-living/explore-the-residencehalls.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two residence halls are located in and around the MetroTech Commons, intended to serve NYU's Brooklyn Campus.\n\nIn 2007, the [[National Association of College and University Residence Halls]] (NACURH) named NYU the National School of the Year for IRHC and [[NRHH]]'s strong efforts over the past year. In addition, NYU was named the National Program of the Year for UltraViolet Live, the annual inter-hall competition that raises funds for [[Relay For Life]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyuirhc.org/what-is-irhc/awards/ |title=Awards |website=Inter-Residence Hall Council |publisher=Inter-Residence Hall Council |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102230425/http://nyuirhc.org/what-is-irhc/awards/ |archivedate=November 2, 2013  }}</ref>\n\n===Sustainability===\nNYU has made the greening of its campus a large priority. For example, NYU has been the largest university purchaser of wind energy in the U.S. since 2009.<ref name=\"Sustainability Fast Facts\">{{cite web | title =NYU Sustainability Fast Facts | publisher =New York University | url =http://www.nyu.edu/sustainability/about.sustainability/fast.facts.html | accessdate =June 8, 2009 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20090412133811/http://www.nyu.edu/sustainability/about.sustainability/fast.facts.html | archive-date =April 12, 2009 | url-status =live }}</ref>\nWith this switch to renewable power, NYU is achieving benefits equivalent to removing 12,000 cars from the road or planting 72,000 trees. In May 2008, the NYU Sustainability Task Force awarded $150,000 in grants to 23 projects that would focus research and efforts toward energy, food, landscape, outreach, procurement, transportation and waste.<ref name=\"At New York University, green is the new violet\">{{cite news | title = At New York University, green is the new violet | newspaper = The Villager | url = http://www.nyu.edu/sustainability/about.sustainability/fast.facts.html | accessdate = June 8, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090412133811/http://www.nyu.edu/sustainability/about.sustainability/fast.facts.html | archive-date = April 12, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref>\nThese projects include a student-led bike-sharing program modeled after Paris' Velib program with 30 bikes free to students, staff, and faculty. NYU received a grade of \"B\" on the College Sustainability Report Card 2010 from the Sustainable Endowments Institute.<ref name=\"Sustainable Endowments Institute Report Card\">{{cite web | title =College Sustainability Report Card 2010 | publisher =Sustainable Endowments Institute | url =http://www.greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/f | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20111006153219/http://www.greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/f | archivedate =October 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nNYU purchased 118 million [[kilowatt-hours]] of [[wind power]] during the 2006\u20132007 academic year \u2013 the largest purchase of wind power by any university in the country and any institution in New York City.<ref name=\"GreenBiz.com\">{{Cite news | title = NYU, Ivy Leagues Top Schools for Green Power | publisher = GreenBiz.com | date = April 19, 2007 | url = http://www.greenbiz.com/news/news_third.cfm?NewsID=34925 | accessdate = September 12, 2007 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012175908/http://greenbiz.com/news/news_third.cfm?NewsID=34925 | archivedate = October 12, 2007 }}</ref> For 2007, the university expanded its purchase of wind power to 132 million kilowatt-hours.<ref name=\"NYU buys more wind power credit\">{{Cite news| title = NYU buys more wind power credit | publisher = Washington Square News | date = November 15, 2007 | url = http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2007/11/15/UniversityNews/Nyu-Buys.More.Wind.Power.Credit-3103146.shtml | accessdate = July 22, 2008 |archivedate=December 1, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201111646/http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2007/11/15/UniversityNews/Nyu-Buys.More.Wind.Power.Credit-3103146.shtml }}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] ranked NYU as one of the greenest colleges in the country in its annual College & University Green Power Challenge.<ref name=\"NYU Office of Public Affairs\">{{cite web | title = NYU to Purchase Wind-Generated Power As Part of New Sustainability Initiative | publisher = NYU Office of Public Affairs | date = October 5, 2006 | url = http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/1235 | accessdate = September 12, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070823234211/http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/1235 | archive-date = August 23, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n=== NYU 2031 ===\nIn 2007, NYU created a strategic plan for a six billion dollar 25 year, {{Convert|6000000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} expansion scheduled to conclude by the universities bicentennial in 2031.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/23/arts/design/23nyu.html|title=N.Y.U. Plans an Expansion of 40 Percent|last=Pogrebin|first=Robin|date=22 March 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=28 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128212624/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/23/arts/design/23nyu.html|archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Details of the plan include {{Convert|2000000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of additional on-campus housing and {{Convert|3500000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} of modern academic spaces spread between NYU's New York City campuses.\n\nThe expansion started in earnest in 2017 with the groundbreaking of [https://www.nyu.edu/about/university-initiatives/academic-space-projects/181-mercer-street.html 181 Mercer Street], a new multi-purpose building that will act as the flagship athletic facility for NYU, while also accompanying a 350-bed Residence Hall, 58 general purpose classrooms and a 350-seat theater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/university-initiatives/academic-space-projects/181-mercer-street.html|title=181 Mercer Street|last=|first=|date=|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723003534/https://www.nyu.edu/about/university-initiatives/academic-space-projects/181-mercer-street.html|archive-date=July 23, 2018|access-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The roughly {{Convert|800000|sqft|m2|adj=on}}, $1.1 billion building is directly adjacent to the south eastern corner of the Washington Square campus and represents a significant focus on the university owner super blocks. Work on the plans second project, [[370 Jay Street]], a {{Convert|500000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} addition to the Brooklyn campus is scheduled to conclude in 2019. The building will house 'the digital arts and sciences' such as the [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]] departments of Computer Science, Electrical and Computer Engineering; the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] Clive Davis Institute for Recorded Music and Game Center and various other NYU initiatives such as the Center for Urban Science and Progress (CUSP) and NYU Wireless (5G research).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/publications/alumni-magazine/fall-2018/features/Brooklyn.html|title=Alumni Magazine Fall 2018|last=|first=|date=|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128211107/https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/publications/alumni-magazine/fall-2018/features/Brooklyn.html|archive-date=November 28, 2018|access-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTo date, NYU has confirmed specific construction details for its NYU 2031 plan to the tune of {{Convert|1300000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} at a cost of $1.6 Billion with roughly 12 years to go until the universities bicentennial. In order to meet the plans outlined goals on time, the university would have to significantly increase spending, fundraising and construction over the next decade.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Admissions and scholarships===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:85%: text-align:center;\"\n|+Global Admission Statistics<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nyu.edu/employees/resources-and-services/administrative-services/institutional-research/factbook.html | title = Factbook | website = NYU | accessdate = August 23, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161226060444/http://www.nyu.edu/employees/resources-and-services/administrative-services/institutional-research/factbook.html | archive-date = December 26, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n! Class of\n!2025\n!2024!! 2023 !! 2022 !! 2021\n|-\n! Applicants\n|\n|85,000+\n| 84,481 ||82,747\n|80,605\n|-\n! Admits\n|\n|13,000\n| 12,307 || 15,722 || 19,233\n|-\n! % Admitted\n|\n|15\n| 16 || 19 ||24\n|-\n! Enrolled\n|\n|6,700\n| 6,500 || 6,469 ||6,721\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|<small>Note: Statistics include NYU's global university network.</small>\n|}\nAdmission to NYU is highly selective. For the undergraduate first-year class of 2024, 15% were admitted from an applicant pool of more than 85,000.<ref name=\":1\" /> The College of Arts and Science had an acceptance rate of 9% and the Stern School of Business had a 7.6% acceptance rate for the class of 2023. \n\nOf those admitted, about 6,500 made up the total enrollment for the class, representing 88 countries and all 50 states. Most freshmen have a typical unweighted GPA of 3.7/A (90\u201395%) and are in the top 10% of their high school graduating class. The median [[SAT]] score was 1500 out of 1600 (within the 99th percentile).<ref name=\":1\" /> The student-to-faculty ratio at the New York campus is 10:1, and less than that at the Abu Dhabi and Shanghai campuses. The average scholarship amount awarded to freshmen is over $35,000, and 18% of freshmen received Pell Grants.<ref name=\"NYU Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/nyu-facts.html|title=NYU Facts|website=New York University|publisher=New York University|accessdate=April 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405121608/https://www.nyu.edu/admissions/undergraduate-admissions/nyu-facts.html|archive-date=April 5, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2016}}, NYU's graduate schools have acceptance rates of 1.8% to the School of Medicine, 23% to the School of Business,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stern.nyu.edu/programs-admissions/full-time-mba/admissions/class-profile|title=NYU Stern &#124; Class Profile|date=|website=Stern.nyu.edu|accessdate=September 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927083644/http://www.stern.nyu.edu/programs-admissions/full-time-mba/admissions/class-profile|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> 28% to the School of Engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-engineering-schools/new-york-university-02120|title=New York University &#124; Best Engineering School &#124; US News|date=|website=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com|accessdate=September 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920063237/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-engineering-schools/new-york-university-02120|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> 29% to the Graduate School of Arts and Science,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-graduate-school-of-arts-and-science-000_10053128.aspx|title=Graduate School of Arts and Science New York University|date=|website=petersons.com|accessdate=October 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220070913/https://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-graduate-school-of-arts-and-science-000_10053128.aspx|archive-date=December 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and 34% to the School of Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com/|title=NYU Law School &#124; Law School Numbers|date=|website=Nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com|accessdate=September 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923113957/http://nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAverage [[MCAT]] score of students at the School of Medicine is 36/45,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.nyu.edu/school/admissions/about-us/student-composition|title=Student Composition &#124; Education and Training|date=|website=Med.nyu.edu|accessdate=September 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927084315/http://www.med.nyu.edu/school/admissions/about-us/student-composition|archive-date=September 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> average [[GMAT]] score of graduate students at the School of Business is 710/800,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> and average [[LSAT]] score of students at the School of Law is 171/180.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com/|title=NYU Law School &#124; Law School Numbers|date=|publisher=Nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com|accessdate=September 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923113957/http://nyu.lawschoolnumbers.com/|archive-date=September 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Schools and leadership ===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=2 style=\"text-align: center;\" | NYU Graduate/Professional Schools\n|-\n| '''College/School''' || '''Established'''\n|-\n|[[New York University School of Law|School of Law]]\n| 1835\n|-\n|[[New York University School of Medicine|School of Medicine]]\n| 1841\n|-\n|[[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]]|| 1854\n|-\n|[[NYU College of Dentistry|College of Dentistry]]\n| 1865\n|-\n|[[NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science|Graduate School of Arts and Science]]\n| 1886\n|-\n|[[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]]|| 1890\n|-\n|[[Leonard N. Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]]|| 1900\n|-\n|[[New York University School of Professional Studies|School of Professional Studies]]|| 1934\n|-\n|[[Robert F. Wagner Graduate School of Public Service]]\n| 1938\n|-\n|[[New York University Rory Meyers College of Nursing|Rory Meyers College of Nursing]]|| 1944\n|-\n|[[New York University School of Social Work|Silver School of Social Work]]|| 1960\n|-\n|[[Tisch School of the Arts]]|| 1965\n|-\n|[[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]]|| 1972\n|-\n|[[Center for Urban Science and Progress]]\n| 2013\n|-\n|[[NYU College of Global Public Health|College of Global Public Health]]\n| 2015\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=2 style=\"text-align: center;\" | NYU Undergraduate Schools\n|-\n| '''College/school''' ||'''Established'''\n|-\n| [[NYU College of Arts and Science|College of Arts and Science]] || 1832\n|-\n| [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]] || 1854\n|-\n| [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]] || 1890\n|-\n| [[Leonard N. Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]] || 1900\n|-\n| [[New York University School of Professional Studies|School of Professional Studies]] || 1934\n|-\n| [[New York University Rory Meyers College of Nursing|Rory Meyers College of Nursing]] || 1944\n|-\n| [[New York University School of Social Work|Silver School of Social Work]] || 1960\n|-\n| [[Tisch School of the Arts]] || 1965\n|-\n| [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]] || 1972\n|-\n| [[NYU Liberal Studies|Global Liberal Studies]] || 2009\n|}\n[[File:NYU-Gallatin School.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Flags identify NYU buildings around the city. This flag is for the [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]].]]\n\nNYU is a private, global, non-sectarian and [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit]] institution of higher education organized into 10 undergraduate schools and 15 graduate/professional schools, with a roughly even split of students between the divisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/academics/schools-and-colleges.html|title=NYU Schools and Colleges|last=|first=|date=|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110013853/https://www.nyu.edu/academics/schools-and-colleges.html|archive-date=January 10, 2019|access-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Arts and Science is currently NYU's largest academic division. It has three subdivisions: the College of Arts and Science, the Graduate School of Arts and Science, and the Liberal Studies program.<ref name=\"Schools and Colleges\" /> The College of Arts and Science and Liberal Studies program are undergraduate divisions, and the former has existed since the founding of NYU.<ref name=\"About CAS\">{{cite web|url=http://cas.nyu.edu/page/aboutcas|title=About CAS|website=NYU College of Arts & Science|publisher=New York University, Arts and Science|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922235954/http://cas.nyu.edu/page/aboutcas|archivedate=September 22, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to NYU, it has created a 'global network university' with its primary campus, two 'portal' campuses, and 12 academic sites. The 'portal' campuses at [[New York University Shanghai|NYU Shanghai]] and [[New York University Abu Dhabi|NYU Abu Dhabi]] function as full-fledged colleges, allowing students to study all four years of their undergraduate studies and receive a degree, never having stepped foot on what would be considered NYU's traditional campus in New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/provost/documents/faculty-global-network/OverviewofGlobalSites%26Portals.pdf|title=NYU's Global Network|last=|first=|date=|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412151409/https://www.nyu.edu/content/dam/nyu/provost/documents/faculty-global-network/OverviewofGlobalSites%26Portals.pdf|archive-date=April 12, 2019|access-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The academic sites at [[Accra]], [[Berlin]], [[Buenos Aires]], [[NYU Florence|Florence]], [[NYU London|London]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Madrid]], [[NYU Paris|Paris]], [[Prague]], [[Sydney]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] function as study away sites, allowing students to spend up to a year away from their home campus. NYU, citing a report by the [[Institute of International Education]], asserts that it has sent more students abroad and brought more international students in than any other university for five continuous years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/november/nyu-is--1-again-in-both-international-students-and-study-abroad.html|title=NYU #1 Again in Both International Students and Study Abroad|last=Beckman|first=John|date=November 13, 2018|website=nyu.edu|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110073858/https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/november/nyu-is--1-again-in-both-international-students-and-study-abroad.html|archive-date=January 10, 2019|access-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[List of Presidents of New York University|The President of New York University]], is selected by the Board of Trustees and serves as the primary executive officer of the university for an unspecified term length. On March 18, 2015, [[Andrew D. Hamilton]] became the 16th and current President of NYU.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/oxford-university-administrator-named-next-nyu-president-1bc048d54ac1|title=Oxford University Administrator Named Next NYU President|last=Local|first=N. Y. U.|date=2015-03-18|website=NYU Local|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> His administration's current objectives include measures of strengthening NYU's science and engineering departments, expanding diversity and inclusionary practices, maintaining its status as a global university and attempting to make the university broadly more affordable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/communications/inauguration-speech-of-andrew-hamilton.html|title=Inauguration Speech of Andrew Hamilton|last=Hamilton|first=Andrew|date=September 25, 2016|access-date=January 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110073829/https://www.nyu.edu/about/leadership-university-administration/office-of-the-president/communications/inauguration-speech-of-andrew-hamilton.html|archive-date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nNYU manages one of the largest annual collegiate research budgets of any university in the United States. In 2017, NYU received $917 million in research grants from the [[National Science Foundation]] alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncsesdata.nsf.gov/profiles/site?method=rankingBySource&ds=herd|title=NSF \u2013 NCSES Academic Institution Profiles \u2013 Rankings by total R&D expenditures|last=|first=|date=|website=Ncsesdata.nsf.gov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113144205/https://ncsesdata.nsf.gov/profiles/site?method=rankingBySource&ds=herd|archive-date=January 13, 2017|accessdate=September 8, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> NYU School of Medicine received $305 million in external research funding from the [[National Institutes of Health]] in 2014. NYU was granted 90 [[patent]]s in 2014, the 19th most of any institution in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/pdf/NAI-IPO-Top-100-Universities-2014.pdf |format=PDF |title=Top 100 Worldwide Universities Granted U.S. Utility Patents |date=2014 |website=Academyofinvestors.org |accessdate=October 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220190405/http://www.academyofinventors.org/pdf/NAI-IPO-Top-100-Universities-2014.pdf |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> NYU owns the fastest [[supercomputer]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2005/august/nyu_acquires_fastest.html|title=NYU Acquires Fastest Supercomputer in New York City|website=Nyu.edu|accessdate=October 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019021352/http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2005/august/nyu_acquires_fastest.html|archive-date=October 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> {{as of|2016}}, NYU hardware researchers and their collaborators enjoy the largest outside funding level for hardware security of any institution in the [[United States]], including grants from the [[National Science Foundation]] (NSF), the [[Office of Naval Research]], the [[Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA), the [[United States Army Research Laboratory]], the [[Air Force Research Laboratory]], the [[Semiconductor Research Corporation]], and companies including [[Twitter]], [[Boeing]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Google]].<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://engineering.nyu.edu/news/2016/10/11/cybersecurity-team-makes-nyu-tandon-crucible-microchip-security |title=Cybersecurity Team Makes NYU Tandon a Crucible for Microchip Security &#124; NYU Tandon School of Engineering |website=Engineering.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=October 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014160632/http://engineering.nyu.edu/news/2016/10/11/cybersecurity-team-makes-nyu-tandon-crucible-microchip-security |archive-date=October 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, four NYU Arts & Science departments ranked in Top 10 of Shanghai [[Academic Ranking of World Universities|Academic Rankings of World Universities]] by Academic Subjects ([[Economics]], [[Politics]], [[Psychology]], and [[Sociology]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/libraries-and-research-centers/leonard-lauder-research-center/programs-and-resources/index-of-cubist-art-collectors/gallatin|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_NU = 22\n| USNWR_NU = 29\n| THE_WSJ = 31\n| USNWR_W = 28\n| ARWU_W = 30\n| Wamo_NU = 107\n| THES_W = 29\n| QS_W = 39\n| Forbes = 35\n}}\n{| class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width: 22em\"\n! colspan=2 class=\"n\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 125%\"|<span class=\"fn\">[[New York University#Schools and colleges|School rankings]]</span>\n|-\n| '''2019 ''U.S. News & World Report'' Rank'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/new-york-university-193900/overall-rankings|title=NYU's Graduate School Rankings|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=August 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816225318/https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/new-york-university-193900/overall-rankings|archive-date=August 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr />\n|-\n| Business  || 10\n|-\n| Education || 10\n|-\n| Engineering || 38\n|-\n| Law || 6\n|-\n| Medicine: Primary Care || 35\n|-\n| Medicine: Research || 4\n|-\n| Nursing: Doctor of Nursing Practice || 19\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's || 17\n|}\n\nNationally, NYU is ranked 20th in the Center for World University Rankings,<ref name=\"cwur.org\">{{cite web |url=https://cwur.org/2018-19.php |title=CWUR World University Rankings 2018-2019 |publisher=Cwur.org |accessdate=April 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180528190852/https://cwur.org/2018-19.php |archive-date=May 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> 17th by ''[[QS World University Rankings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020#sorting=rank+region=+country=257+faculty=+stars=false+search=|title=QS World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=Top Universities|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120917171555/http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/universitat-autonoma-de-barcelona#sorting=rank+region=+country=257+faculty=+stars=false+search=|archive-date=September 17, 2012|access-date=}}</ref> 22nd in the ''[[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]'', 27th by ''[[Business Insider]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/best-colleges-in-america-ranked-2018-9|title=The top 50 colleges in the United States, ranked|first=Rachel|last=Premack|website=Business Insider|accessdate=May 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507202557/https://www.businessinsider.com/best-colleges-in-america-ranked-2018-9|archive-date=May 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and 29th by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.\n\nGlobally, NYU is ranked 25th in the Center for World University Rankings,<ref name=\"cwur.org\"/> 16th in International Colleges and Universities,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.4icu.org/top200/ |title=Top 200 Universities in the World |publisher=4icu.org |accessdate=April 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901183434/http://www.4icu.org/top200/ |archive-date=September 1, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 32nd in the ''Academic Ranking of World Universities'', 27th in the ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2018/world-ranking#!/page/1/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title=World University Rankings|date=August 18, 2017|publisher=|access-date=December 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906013321/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2018/world-ranking#!/page/1/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|archive-date=September 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and 39th in the ''QS World University Rankings''. Additionally, NYU is ranked 26th in the ''Times Higher Education World University Rankings'' Reputation Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/new-york-university|title=New York University|work=Times Higher Education|access-date=September 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118084102/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/new-york-university|archive-date=January 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''U.S. News & World Report'' ranks NYU's graduate schools 6th for law, 10th for public policy, 9th for math (1st for applied math<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/applied-mathematics-rankings |title=Best Applied Mathematics Programs - Top Math Schools - US News Best Graduate Schools |work=rankingsandreviews.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101230848/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/applied-mathematics-rankings |archivedate=November 1, 2013  }}</ref>), 8th for [[Occupational therapy]] under [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]], 10th for business, 11th for economics, 12th for political science, 4th for medical school research, 10th for education, 19th for nursing doctorate, 38th for physical therapy, 30th for computer science, 36th for psychology, and 38th for engineering.<ref name=\"NYU_Rankings_USNWR_G\">{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools |title=Best Graduate Schools |publisher=U.S. News & World Report LP |accessdate=April 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424191236/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools |archivedate=April 24, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nGlobally, NYU's social sciences are ranked 8th by the ''Academic Ranking of World Universities'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSOC2015.html |title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Social Science - 2015 |work=[[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] |accessdate=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007080259/http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSOC2015.html |archive-date=October 7, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> 15th by the ''Times Higher Education World University Rankings'',<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/new-york-university?ranking-dataset=1089 |title=Top 100 universities for social sciences 2015 |magazine=Times Higher Education |accessdate=October 1, 2015 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006213018/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/new-york-university?ranking-dataset=1089 |archive-date=October 6, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> and 16th by the ''QS World University Rankings''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/new-york-university-nyu#wur |title=QS World University Rankings by Faculty 2015 \u2013 Social Sciences and Management |publisher=Top Universities |date=August 28, 2015 |accessdate=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004162643/http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/new-york-university-nyu#wur |archive-date=October 4, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> NYU is globally ranked 11th for psychology by the ''QS World University Ranking''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/psychology |title=New York University (NYU) Rankings |publisher=Top Universities |accessdate=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923161111/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/psychology |archive-date=September 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Social Psychology Network]] ranks NYU 5th for industrial/organizational psychology, 14th for clinical psychology,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.socialpsychology.org/ggradoth.htm |title=Ranking of U.S. Psychology Ph.D. Programs by Area |publisher=Socialpsychology.org |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727035538/http://www.socialpsychology.org/ggradoth.htm |archive-date=July 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''U.S. News & World Report'' ranks NYU 9th for social psychology and 9th for behavioral neuroscience.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-humanities-schools/new-york-university-193900 |title=New York University &#124; Best Social Sciences & Humanities School &#124; US News |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909112121/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-humanities-schools/new-york-university-193900 |archive-date=September 9, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''U.S. News & World Report'' ranks the [[New York University School of Law]] 1st for tax law and 1st for international law. The publication also ranks The [[Robert F. Wagner Graduate School of Public Service]] 10th in public policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/new-york-university-03110 |title=New York University &#124; Best Law School &#124; US News |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813225803/http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/new-york-university-03110 |archive-date=August 13, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[NYU Department of Philosophy]] is globally ranked 1st by ''[[The Philosophical Gourmet Report]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophicalgourmet.com|title=The Philosophical Gourmet|year=2011|publisher=Blackwell Publishing Philosophy|access-date=August 19, 2005|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20100813140338/http://www.philosophicalgourmet.com/|archive-date=August 13, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> and the ''QS World University Rankings''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/philosophy#sorting=rank+region=+country=+faculty=+stars=false+search= |title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2015 \u2013 Philosophy |publisher=Top Universities |date=September 15, 2015 |accessdate=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929065545/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2015/philosophy#sorting=rank+region=+country=+faculty=+stars=false+search= |archive-date=September 29, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> NYU is ranked 1st for New Ivies by college resource guide [[Unigo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/unigo/top-10-new-ivies-2013_b_1844804.html |title=Unigo: Top 10 New Ivies 2013 |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=August 30, 2012 |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010184014/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/unigo/top-10-new-ivies-2013_b_1844804.html |archive-date=October 10, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2006, NYU was named by [[Kaplan, Inc.|Kaplan]] as one of the \"New Ivies.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|title=America's 25 New Elite 'Ivies' |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |date=August 21, 2006 |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/14325172/site/newsweek/ |accessdate=July 16, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708135928/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/14325172/site/newsweek/ |archivedate=July 8, 2007 }}</ref> The annual Global Employability Survey in [[The New York Times]] ranks NYU 11th nationally and 29th globally for employability.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2013/10/28/education/28iht-educlede28-graphic.html |title=Education \u2013 Image |newspaper=NYTimes.com |date=October 28, 2013 |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031001520/http://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2013/10/28/education/28iht-educlede28-graphic.html |archive-date=October 31, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://emerging.fr/rank_en.html |title=Emerging Employability University Ranking |publisher=Emerging.fr |date=January 1, 1980 |accessdate=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217033507/http://emerging.fr/rank_en.html |archive-date=February 17, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> NYU is consistently ranked as a \"Top 10 Dream College\" for both parents and students according to [[The Princeton Review]]. Alongside [[Stanford University]], [[Harvard College]], [[Princeton University]], and [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], NYU is one of few universities to regularly appear in the top 10 list for both parents and students.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.princetonreview.com/press/college-hopes-worries-press-release |title=The Princeton Review's 2019 College Hopes & Worries Survey Reports on 11,900 Students' & Parents' \"Dream\" Colleges and Application Perspectives |work=The Princeton Review |date=March 6, 2019 |access-date=April 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730131920/http://www.princetonreview.com/press/college-hopes-worries-press-release |archive-date=July 30, 2016 |url-status=dead }}<br /></ref> NYU ranks 19th in the world based on the number of patents generated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/pdf/NAI-IPO-Top-100-Universities-2014.pdf |format=PDF |title=Top 100 Worldwide Universities Granted U.S. Utility Patents |date=2014 |website=Academyofinvestors.org |accessdate=August 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220190405/http://www.academyofinventors.org/pdf/NAI-IPO-Top-100-Universities-2014.pdf |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGlobally, NYU is ranked 7th by the Times Higher Education World University Rankings for producing alumni who are millionaires, 5th among universities with the highest number of alumni worth $30 million or more, and 4th by Wealth-X for producing ultra high net-worth and billionaire alumni.<ref name=\"Times Higher Education\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/worlds-top-100-universities-for-producing-millionaires/2008749.article|title=World's top 100 universities for producing millionaires|work=Times Higher Education|access-date=August 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115105352/https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/financial-times-executive-mba-ranking-2015-top-100|archive-date=January 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"abc\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/top-15-universities-wealthy-alumni/story?id=18539608#5|title=Top 15 Universities With the Most Wealthy Alumni|work=ABC News|access-date=September 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630103045/http://abcnews.go.com/Business/top-15-universities-wealthy-alumni/story?id=18539608#5|archive-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNBC News\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100475323|title=Billionaire U: Why Harvard Mints Mega-Rich Alums|work=CNBC News|access-date=September 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815030219/https://www.cnbc.com/id/100475323|archive-date=August 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"wealthx\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wealthx.com/report/major-gift-fundraising-potential-global-uhnw-alumni-report/|title=Major Gift Fundraising Potential: Global UHNW Alumni Report - Wealth-X|work=Wealth-X|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725153548/https://www.wealthx.com/report/major-gift-fundraising-potential-global-uhnw-alumni-report/|archive-date=July 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Student government===\nThe Student Government Assembly (SGA) is the [[students' union|governing student body]] at NYU. The SGA has been involved in controversial debates on campus, including a campus-wide ban on the sale of [[Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola products]] in 2005, and the [[Graduate Student Organizing Committee]] unionization in 2001 and subsequent strike in 2005.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Coca-Cola given ultimatum |first=Barbara |last=Leonard |url=http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/04/NewscampusNews/CocaCola.Given.Ultimatum-2387167.shtml |newspaper=[[Washington Square News]] |date=November 4, 2005 |accessdate=October 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113000715/http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/04/NewscampusNews/CocaCola.Given.Ultimatum-2387167.shtml |archivedate=January 13, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/06_04/b3968078.htm |title=How NYU Chose Colombia over Coke |first=Elizabeth |last=Woyke |newspaper=[[Business Week]] |date=January 23, 2006 |accessdate=October 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808180450/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/06_04/b3968078.htm |archivedate=August 8, 2007  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = A Big Breakthrough for T.A. Unions | first = Scott | last = Smallwood | url = http://chronicle.com/weekly/v47/i27/27a01001.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080424041905/http://chronicle.com/weekly/v47/i27/27a01001.htm| archivedate=April 24, 2008| newspaper = [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]] | date = March 16, 2001 | accessdate = October 12, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=NYU graduate assistants pledge to continue strike |first=Richard M. |last=Coe III |url=http://media.www.dailytarheel.com/media/storage/paper885/news/2005/12/06/StateNational/Nyu-Graduate.Assistants.Pledge.To.Continue.Strike-1368324.shtml |newspaper=[[Daily Tar Heel]] |date=December 6, 2005 |accessdate=October 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210230240/http://media.www.dailytarheel.com/media/storage/paper885/news/2005/12/06/StateNational/Nyu-Graduate.Assistants.Pledge.To.Continue.Strike-1368324.shtml |archivedate=February 10, 2009 }}</ref> This ban was lifted by the University Senate on February 5, 2009.<ref>{{Cite book| url = http://www.nyunews.com/news/university/coke_ban_lifted-1.1356379 | first = Sergio | last = Hernandez | publisher = [[Washington Square News]] | title = Coke ban lifted | date = February 5, 2009 | accessdate = February 8, 2009 |archivedate=February 7, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207072456/http://nyunews.com/news/university/coke_ban_lifted-1.1356379 }}</ref> SGA consists of 75 voting members from subsidiary student government organs including the [[Student Senators Council of New York University|Student Senators Council (SSC)]] and the Presidents Council, which are elected from their respective individual undergraduate and graduate colleges.\n\nIn 2018, the structure of the universities student government was called into question by numerous students through school newspapers and social media pages calling for \"sweeping changes to its byzantine structure.\" Advocates claimed the structure of SGA failed to represent all students, wasted university funds and operated in an undemocratic manner. Opponents claimed that advocates were merely motivated by legislation supporting the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]] movement that was likely to pass.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nyulocal.com/facebook-page-calling-for-sweeping-changes-to-sga-35d9e3097d98|title=\"OurSGA-NYU\" Facebook Page Calls for Sweeping Changes to Student Government|last=Pilgreen|first=Justin|date=December 6, 2018|work=NYU Local|access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Student organizations===\n[[File:AcademyBus2145NYU.jpg|alt=|thumb|A bus system transports students to and from the far ends of campus.]]\nNYU has over 450 student clubs and organizations on campus.<ref>{{cite web | title = New York University:Housing & Campus Life | year = 2007 | publisher = [[College Board]] | url = http://collegesearch.collegeboard.com/search/CollegeDetail.jsp?collegeId=3186&profileId=8 | accessdate = October 10, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070821000153/http://collegesearch.collegeboard.com/search/CollegeDetail.jsp?collegeId=3186&profileId=8 | archive-date = August 21, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> In addition to the sports teams, fraternities, sororities, and study clubs, there are many organizations on campus that focus on entertainment, arts, and culture.\n\n==== Journalism, media, and broadcast organizations ====\nThese organizations include various [[student newspaper|student media]] clubs: for instance, the daily [[student newspaper]] the ''[[Washington Square News]]'', the ''[[NYU Local]]'' daily blog, ''[[The Plague (magazine)|The Plague]]'' comedy magazine, \"''Washington Square Local'' web-based satire news source, and the literary journals ''[[Washington Square Review]]'' and ''The Minetta Review'', as well as student-run event producers such as the NYU Program Board and the Inter-Residence Hall Council. It also operates [[radio station]] [[WNYU-FM]] 89.1 with a diverse [[college radio]] format, transmitting to the entire [[New York metropolitan area]] from the original campus, and via booster station WNYU-FM1 which fills in the signal in [[lower Manhattan]] from atop one of the Silver Towers, next to the [[American football field|football field]] at the Washington Square campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/student-life/getting-involved/clubs-and-organizations.html |title=Clubs and Organizations |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200710/http://www.nyu.edu/life/student-life/getting-involved/clubs-and-organizations.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.osa.nyu.edu/directory/club_directory_alias.php |title=Club Directory |website=Center for Student Activities, Leadership & Service |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925014812/http://www.osa.nyu.edu/directory/club_directory_alias.php |archive-date=September 25, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStudents publish a campus comedy magazine, ''The Plague''. Like many [[college humor magazines]], this often pokes fun at [[popular culture]] as well as campus life and the idiosyncrasies of New York University.<ref name=\"Medley\">{{cite web|url=http://alumni.nyu.edu/s/1068/index.aspx?sid=1068&gid=1&pgid=1617|title=New York University - Archivist's Angle: The Medley|website=Alumni.nyu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304194200/http://www.alumni.nyu.edu/s/1068/index.aspx?sid=1068&gid=1&pgid=1617|archive-date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=February 17, 2016}}</ref> ''The Plague'' was founded in 1978<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/clubs/plague/history.shtml|title=History of The Plague|website=Ny.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830152657/http://www.nyu.edu/clubs/plague/history.shtml|archive-date=August 30, 2013|accessdate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> by Howard Ostrowsky along with Amy Burns, John Rawlins, Joe Pinto and Dan Fiorella,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.danfiorella.com/easy-as-falling-off-a-blog/memories-of-the-plague|title=Memories of The Plague|work=Dan Fiorella: Writer @ large|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606223730/http://www.danfiorella.com/easy-as-falling-off-a-blog/memories-of-the-plague|archive-date=June 6, 2014|access-date=June 19, 2014}}</ref> and is currently published once per semester.<ref name=\"Plague\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/clubs/plague/|title=The Plague|website=Ny.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054624/http://www.nyu.edu/clubs/plague/|archive-date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> It is not NYU's first humor magazine, as ''The Medley'' was a humor magazine published by the [[Eucleian Society]] from 1913 to 1950.<ref name=\"Medley\" />\n\n==== Mock trial team ====\nThe New York University Mock Trial team is consistently ranked as one of the best collegiate mock trial teams in the country. NYU has qualified for the National Championship Tournament for 10 consecutive seasons and placed in the top 10 during each of those years. In the 2009\u20132010 season, NYU won the 26th National Championship Tournament in Memphis over rival [[Harvard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2010/04/22/nyu-crowned-national-college-mock-trial-champion.html|title=NYU Crowned National Mock Trial Champion|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=October 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119124334/http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2010/04/22/nyu-crowned-national-college-mock-trial-champion.html|archive-date=November 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The following season, they qualified for the final round once more only to be the runners-up to [[UCLA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailybruin.com/2011/04/25/ucla_mock_trial_team_takes_first_at_american_mock_trial_association_27th_national_championship_tourn/|title=UCLA Mock Trial team takes first at American Mock Trial Association 27th National Championship Tournament|work=dailybruin.com|access-date=October 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119182704/http://dailybruin.com/2011/04/25/ucla_mock_trial_team_takes_first_at_american_mock_trial_association_27th_national_championship_tourn/|archive-date=November 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the American Mock Trial Association's 2015\u20132016 power rankings, NYU ranks third, behind Harvard and [[Yale]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegemocktrial.org/2015-16%20AMTA%20TPR.pdf |format=PDF |title=AMERICAN MOCK TRIAL ASSOCIATION : 2015-2016 TEAM POWER RANKINGS |website=Collegemocktrial.org |accessdate=August 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329015631/http://www.collegemocktrial.org/2015-16%20AMTA%20TPR.pdf |archive-date=March 29, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== Campus traditions ====\nNYU has traditions which have persisted across campuses. Since the beginning of the 20th century initiation ceremonies have welcomed incoming NYU freshmen. At the Bronx University Heights Campus, seniors used to grab unsuspecting freshmen, take them to a horse-watering trough, and then dunk them head-first into what was known colloquially as \"the Fountain of Knowledge.\" This underground initiation took place until the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Friss | first = Evan | title = Chronicles: A Look at NYU's Past | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | newspaper = NYU Today | date = September 13, 2004 | url = http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/18/01/Stories/chronicles-18-01.html | accessdate = July 17, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070812235317/http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/18/01/Stories/chronicles-18-01.html | archive-date = August 12, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> Today freshmen take part in university-sponsored activities during what is called \"Welcome Week.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyu.edu/life/events-traditions/welcome-week.html |title=Welcome Week |website=New York University |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102200851/http://www.nyu.edu/life/events-traditions/welcome-week.html |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, throughout the year the university traditionally holds Apple Fest (an apple-themed country fest that began at the University Heights campus), the Violet Ball (a dance in the atrium of Bobst Library), Strawberry Fest (featuring New York City's longest [[Shortcake|Strawberry Shortcake]]), and the semi-annual [[midnight breakfast]] where Student Affairs administrators serve free breakfast to students before [[final examination|finals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://inlikeme.com/new-york-university/ |title=New York University |website=In Like Me |publisher=InlikeMe and Phrazorp LLC |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102210314/http://inlikeme.com/new-york-university/ |archive-date=November 2, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Greek life===\nSome of the first [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternities]] in the country were formed at NYU.<ref name=\"psiupsilon\"/><ref name=\"alphaepsilonpi\"/> [[Fraternities and sororities|Greek life]] first formed on the NYU campus in 1837 when [[Psi Upsilon]] chartered its Delta Chapter.<ref name=\"psiupsilon\">{{cite web| title = Psi Upsilon History | year = 2006 | publisher = Psi Upsilon Fraternity | url = http://www.psiu.org/fr/history.html | accessdate = July 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070414185849/http://www.psiu.org/fr/history.html |archivedate = April 14, 2007}}</ref> The first fraternities at NYU were social ones. With their athletic, professional, intellectual, and service activities, later groups sought to attract students who also formed other groups. Since then, Greek letter organizations have proliferated to include 25 social fraternities and sororities. {{as of|2014}}, approximately 13% of NYU students are members of fraternities or sororities.<ref>{{cite web | title = New York University: Campus Life | work = US News & World Report | year = 2014 | accessdate = March 20, 2014 | url = http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/new-york-university-2785 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140220200404/http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/new-york-university-2785 | archive-date = February 20, 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nFour governing boards oversee Greek life at the university. The Interfraternity Council (IFC) has jurisdiction over all twelve recognized fraternities on campus. Eight sororities are under the jurisdiction of the Panhellenic Council (PhC), which features seven national sororities (\u0394\u03a6\u0395, \u0391\u0395\u03a6, \u0391\u03a3\u03a4, \u03a0\u0392\u03a6, \u039a\u039a\u0393, \u0396\u03a4\u0391, \u0394\u0393) and two local sororities (\u0391\u03a6\u0396 and \u0398\u03a6\u0392). Five multicultural organizations maintain membership in the Multicultural Greek Council (MGC), including two fraternities and three sororities. All three of the aforementioned boards are managed under the auspices of the Inter-Greek Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyu-igc.weebly.com/who-we-are.html |title=Who We Are |website=Inter-Greek Council |publisher=New York University Inter-Greek Council |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103120720/http://nyu-igc.weebly.com/who-we-are.html |archive-date=November 3, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGreek organizations have historical significance at NYU. [[Delta Phi Epsilon (social)|Delta Phi Epsilon]], [[Zeta Psi]], [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]], [[Tau Delta Phi]],<ref>{{cite web| title = Our History | publisher = Tau Delta Phi Fraternity, Inc. | year = 2007 | url = http://www.taudeltaphifraternity.org/history.php | accessdate = October 20, 2008 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080920030110/http://www.taudeltaphifraternity.org/history.php <!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate = September 20, 2008}}</ref> [[Alpha Kappa Psi]] and [[Delta Sigma Pi]] were founded at NYU. Zeta Psi was chartered in 1847,<ref name=\"alphaepsilonpi\">{{cite web| first = Jared | last = Sunshine | title = History | year = 2007 | publisher = Zeta Psi Fraternity of North America, Inc. | url = http://www.zetapsi.org/history.php | accessdate = July 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070729224238/http://www.zetapsi.org/history.php |archivedate = July 29, 2007}}</ref> [[Delta Sigma Pi]] in 1907,<ref name=\"deltsigmapi\">{{cite web| title = History | year = 2008 | publisher = International Business Fraternity of Delta Sigma Pi | url = http://www.dspnet.org/site/about_us/history.asp | accessdate = April 25, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080319093432/http://www.dspnet.org/site/about_us/history.asp |archivedate = March 19, 2008}}</ref> [[Alpha Epsilon Pi]] in 1913,<ref>{{cite web| title = History \u2013 Alpha Epsilon Pi | publisher = Kintera, Inc. | url = http://www.aepi.org/site/pp.asp?c=geJQIUOwErH&b=2117019 | accessdate = July 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070523171037/http://www.aepi.org/site/pp.asp?c=geJQIUOwErH&b=2117019 |archivedate = May 23, 2007}}</ref> and [[Alpha Phi Omega]] in 1938.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aponyu.org|title=Alpha Phi Omega NYU {{!}} Beta Iota Chapter|website=Alpha Phi Omega NYU {{!}} Beta Iota Chapter|access-date=April 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423034123/https://www.aponyu.org/|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Delta Phi Epsilon was founded in 1917.<ref>{{cite web| title = History and Traditions | publisher = Delta Phi Epsilon International Sorority | url = http://www.dphie.org/general/index.shtml | accessdate = July 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070628142321/http://www.dphie.org/general/index.shtml |archivedate = June 28, 2007}}</ref> The NYU Gamma chapter of [[Delta Phi]], founded in 1841, is the longest continuously active fraternity chapter in the world, having never gone inactive since its establishment. Delta Phi is also the oldest continuously active fraternity in the United States, being the only organization in the original Union Triad to remain active since its institute.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dphinyu.com/dphinyu.com/About.html |title=About |website=Delta Phi Gamma Chapter |publisher=NYU Delta Phi Gamma Chapter |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102054638/http://www.dphinyu.com/dphinyu.com/About.html |archivedate=November 2, 2013  }}</ref> The NYU Gamma chapter of [[Zeta Beta Tau]] is the oldest active \u0396\u0392\u03a4 chapter in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyuzbt.com/#rush |title=Rush FAQ'S |website=Zeta Beta Tau Gamma Chapter |publisher=NYU Zeta Beta Tau Gamma Chapter |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102123023/http://nyuzbt.com/#rush |archivedate=November 2, 2013  }}</ref>\n\n=== Secret societies ===\nDuring the University Heights era, an apparent rift evolved with some organizations distancing themselves from students from the downtown schools. The exclusive [[Philomathean Society at New York University|Philomathean Society]] operated from 1832 to 1888 (formally giving way in 1907 and reconstituted into the [[Andiron Club]]). Included among the Andiron's regulations was \"Rule No.11: Have no relations save the most casual and informal kind with the downtown schools.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/eadapp/transform?source=archives/andiron.xml&style=archives/archives.xsl|title=Guide to the Andiron Club of New York City|work=|publisher=New York University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817042434/http://dlib.nyu.edu/eadapp/transform?source=archives%2Fandiron.xml&style=archives%2Farchives.xsl|archive-date=August 17, 2007|accessdate=July 17, 2007}}</ref> [[The Eucleian Society]], rival to the Philomathean Society, was founded in 1832. The [[Knights of the Lamp]] was a social organization founded in 1914 at the School of Commerce. This organization met every full moon and had a glowworm as its mascot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/thenandnow/leisure.html|title=A Window Into the Past: NYU in Retrospect|work=|publisher=New York University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070618072029/http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/thenandnow/leisure.html|archive-date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=July 15, 2007}}</ref> The [[Red Dragon Society]], founded in 1898, is thought to be the most selective society at NYU.\n\nIn addition, NYU's first [[yearbook]] was formed by fraternities and \"secret societies\" at the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/test/175/pages/year.htm|title=175 Facts About NYU|work=|publisher=New York University Archives|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012185430/http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/test/175/pages/year.htm|archive-date=October 12, 2007|accessdate=July 15, 2007}}</ref> There have been several attempts to restart old societies by both former and incoming undergraduate classes.\n\n=== ROTC ===\nNYU does not have an ROTC program on campus. However, NYU students may participate in the [[U.S. Army ROTC]] program through NYC Army ROTC, headquartered at [[Fordham University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nyu.edu/admissions/financial-aid-and-scholarships/frequently-asked-questions.html|title=Frequently Asked Questions|author=NYU Web Communications|work=nyu.edu|access-date=April 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501155321/http://www.nyu.edu/admissions/financial-aid-and-scholarships/frequently-asked-questions.html|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{Main|NYU Violets}}\n\nNYU's sports teams are referred to as the [[NYU Violets]], the colors being the trademarked hue \"NYU Violet\" and white. Since 1981, the school [[mascot]] has been a bobcat, whose origin can be traced back to the abbreviation then being used by the Bobst Library computerized catalog\u2014short: Bobcat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/athletics/clubs/mascots/history.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612225016/http://www.nyu.edu/athletics/clubs/mascots/history.html|archivedate=June 12, 2007 |title=History of the Bobcat |publisher=New York University|accessdate=December 29, 2010}}</ref> NYU's sports teams include baseball, men's and women's varsity basketball, cross country, fencing, golf, soccer, softball, swimming and diving, tennis, track and field, volleyball, and wrestling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gonyuathletics.com/|title=NYU Athletics|publisher=New York University|accessdate=April 22, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414084536/http://www.gonyuathletics.com/|archive-date=April 14, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Most of NYU's sports teams participate in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA's]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] and the [[University Athletic Association]], while fencing and ice hockey participate in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]].<ref>{{cite web | title = The Organization | publisher = National Intercollegiate Women's Fencing Association | url = http://www.niwfa.com/ | accessdate = July 17, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070607172853/http://www.niwfa.com/ | archive-date = June 7, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://achahockey.org/view/achahockey/acha-hockey-news/news_464320|title=ACHA Approves New York University to Men\u2019s Division 1 {{!}} ACHA|website=achahockey.org|access-date=2018-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113025709/http://achahockey.org/view/achahockey/acha-hockey-news/news_464320|archive-date=November 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/rankings/icehockey-men/d1/rpi|title=DI Men's Ice Hockey Rankings - RPI {{!}} NCAA.com|website=www.ncaa.com|access-date=2018-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113075448/https://www.ncaa.com/rankings/icehockey-men/d1/rpi|archive-date=November 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> While NYU has had [[All-American]] football players, the school has not had a varsity [[American football|football]] team since 1952.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nyulocal.com/on-campus/2012/04/19/we-are-the-champions-sometimes-the-highs-and-lows-of-nyu-athletics-2/ |title=We Are The Champions, Sometimes: The Highs And Lows Of NYU Athletics |last1=Kleeman |first1=Sophie |date=April 19, 2012 |website=NYU Local |publisher=New York University |accessdate=October 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101195859/http://nyulocal.com/on-campus/2012/04/19/we-are-the-champions-sometimes-the-highs-and-lows-of-nyu-athletics-2/ |archive-date=November 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNYU students also compete in club and intramural sports, including [[badminton]], [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[Rowing (sport)|crew]], [[cycling]], [[equestrianism]], [[ice hockey]], [[lacrosse]], [[martial arts]], [[rugby football|rugby]], [[softball]], [[Squash (sport)|squash]], [[tennis]], [[triathlon]], and [[Ultimate (sport)|ultimate]]. The [http://gonyuathletics.com/index.aspx?path=palladium Palladium Athletic Facility] serves as the home base of NYU's Varsity and Club intercollegiate athletic teams, while NYU's 404 and Brooklyn athletic facilities offer additional space for the NYU fitness community. Many of NYU's varsity teams play their games at various facilities and fields throughout Manhattan because of the scarcity of space for playing fields near campus. NYU is currently in the process of building a new billion dollar flagship athletic facility known as [https://www.nyu.edu/about/university-initiatives/academic-space-projects/181-mercer-street.html 181 Mercer Street]. When complete, the new home of NYU Athletics will host a six-lane swimming pool, four full basketball courts, a complete in-door running track and other sports related offerings.\n\n== Notable faculty ==\n{{Main|List of New York University faculty|}}\n \n==Notable alumni==\n{{Main|List of New York University alumni|}}\n<gallery mode=\"nolines\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Jack Dorsey 2014.jpg|[[Jack Dorsey]], American billionaire and internet entrepreneur, founder and CEO of [[Twitter]] and [[Square, Inc.]]; [[New York University College of Arts & Science|CAS]] (dropped out)\nFile:Herb Kelleher.jpg|[[Herb Kelleher]], American billionaire airline businessman and lawyer; co-founder, later [[Chief executive officer|CEO]], and chairman emeritus of [[Southwest Airlines]]; [[New York University School of Law|Law]] '56\nFile:Bjorgolfur Thor Bjorgolfsson til debatarrangenmentet Thors Saga - hvordan kommer Island videre? (1).jpg|[[Bj\u00f6rg\u00f3lfur Thor Bj\u00f6rg\u00f3lfsson|Thor Bj\u00f6rg\u00f3lfsson]], Icelandic billionare and investor; chairman of [[Novator Partners]]; [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern]] '91\nFile:Director Robert S. Mueller- III.jpg|[[Robert Mueller|Robert Muller III]], American public official; lead director of the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation]], author of the [[Mueller Report]], former [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation|Director]] of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]]; [[New York University Graduate School of Arts and Science|GSAS]] '67\nFile:Alan Greenspan color photo portrait.jpg|[[Alan Greenspan]], American economist and public official; former long-time [[Chair of the Federal Reserve|Chairman]] of the [[Federal Reserve]]; [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern]] '48, '50, '77\nFile:Bill de Blasio Blue Room City Hall NYC.jpg|[[Bill de Blasio]], American politician; current mayor of [[New York City]]; former [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|2020 Democratic Party presidential candidate]]; [[New York University College of Arts & Science|CAS]] '83\nFile:Rudy Giuliani (cropped).jpg|[[Rudy Giuliani]], American politician; current Attorney to [[President of the United States|President]]