{"title_page": "Christian Mayrleb", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian retired footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Christian Mayrleb\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Christian Mayrleb\n| height         = 1.76 m\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1972|6|8}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wels]], Austria\n| currentclub    = ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz (Manager)\n| clubnumber     = \n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1981\u20131991 | youthclubs1 = [[FC Linz|SK VOEST Linz]]\n| years1         = 1992\u20131993 | clubs1 = [[FC Linz|Stahl Linz]] | caps1 = 2 | goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1993\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[SV Ried]] | caps2 = 76 | goals2 = 35\n| years3         = 1994\u20131996 | clubs3 = [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira/Wacker]] | caps3 = 66 | goals3 = 15\n| years4         = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[FC Tirol Innsbruck]] | caps4 = 53 | goals4 = 17\n| years5         = 1998 | clubs5 = [[Sheffield Wednesday]] | caps5 = 3 | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1998\u20132002 | clubs6 = [[Austria Vienna]] | caps6 = 134 | goals6 = 65\n| years7         = 2003\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[SV Pasching]] | caps7 = 75 | goals7 = 38\n| years8         = 2005\u20132006 | clubs8 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] | caps8 = 28 | goals8 = 7\n| years9         = 2006\u20132007 | clubs9 = [[SV Pasching]] | caps9 = 30 | goals9 = 11\n| years10        = 2007\u20132010 | clubs10 = [[LASK Linz]] | caps10 = 108 | goals10 = 33\n| years11        = 2011 | clubs11 =[[FC Pasching]] | caps11 = 9 | goals11 = 3\n| totalcaps = 584 | totalgoals = 224\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132005 | nationalteam1 = [[Austria national football team|Austria]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 30 | nationalgoals1 = 6\n| manageryears1  = 2012 | managerclubs1 = ATSV Stadl-Paura (sporting director)\n| manageryears2  = 2012\u20132016 | managerclubs2 = ATSV Stadl-Paura\n| manageryears3  = 2016\u20132018 | managerclubs3 = ASK\u00d6 Oedt\n| manageryears4  = 2019\u2013     | managerclubs4 = ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz\n}}\n\n'''Christian Mayrleb''' (born 8 June 1972) is an Austrian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who is currently employed as the manager of Austrian side ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz.<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/coaches/christian-mayrleb/11167/</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Wels]], [[Upper Austria]], Mayrleb started his professional career at [[Austrian Football First League|Second Division]] side Stahl Linz and [[SV Ried]] before joining [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|First level]] outfit [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira/Wacker]] at the start of the 1994/1995 season. He then played for [[FC Tirol Innsbruck]] where he was snapped up by English [[Premier League]] club [[Sheffield Wednesday]], only to return to Austria after half a season on the subs' bench.\nHe moved to Vienna giants [[Austria Vienna]] for a prolific 4 years before moving on to play for [[SV Pasching]], [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] and ending up in [[Linz]] again with [[LASK|LASK Linz]].\n\nIn November 2006 Mayrleb failed a drug test but was cleared by a League disciplinary panel because no evidence was found he was taking performance-enhancing drugs.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=soccer&id=2668506 Austrian league clears Mayrleb of doping] - ESPN Sports</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHe made his debut for [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in an August 1998 friendly match against [[France national football team|France]] and came on as a substitute in his first six matches for the national team. He scored his first goal two months after his debut game. He earned 29 caps, scoring 6 goals. His last international was a September 2005 World Cup qualification match against [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]].\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[Austrian Bundesliga Top Goalscorer]] (1):'''\n** 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oberliga-a.at/fussball_a/torschutzen_a.htm |title=\u00d6sterreichs Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige |publisher=www.oberliga-a.at |accessdate=2008-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915044827/http://www.oberliga-a.at/fussball_a/torschutzen_a.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|11022}}\n*[http://www.austria-archiv.at/spieler.php?Spieler_ID=30 Profile] - Austria Archive\n*{{NFT player|8668}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|11022<!-- -christian-mayrleb -->}}\n\n{{Austrian Football Bundesliga top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayrleb, Christian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wels]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Austrian footballers]]\n[[Category:Austrian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Austria international footballers]]\n[[Category:SV Ried players]]\n[[Category:FC Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling players]]\n[[Category:FC Wacker Innsbruck players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FK Austria Wien players]]\n[[Category:FC Red Bull Salzburg players]]\n[[Category:LASK Linz players]]\n[[Category:FC Juniors O\u00d6 players]]\n[[Category:Austrian Football Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian retired footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Christian Mayrleb\n| image          =\n| fullname       = Christian Mayrleb\n| height         = 1.76 m\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1972|6|8}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wels]], Austria\n| currentclub    = ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz (Manager)\n| clubnumber     = \n| position       = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]\n| youthyears1    = 1981\u20131991 | youthclubs1 = [[FC Linz|SK VOEST Linz]]\n| years1         = 1992\u20131993 | clubs1 = [[FC Linz|Stahl Linz]] | caps1 = 2 | goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1993\u20131994 | clubs2 = [[SV Ried]] | caps2 = 76 | goals2 = 35\n| years3         = 1994\u20131996 | clubs3 = [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira/Wacker]] | caps3 = 66 | goals3 = 15\n| years4         = 1996\u20131997 | clubs4 = [[FC Tirol Innsbruck]] | caps4 = 53 | goals4 = 17\n| years5         = 1998 | clubs5 = [[Sheffield Wednesday]] | caps5 = 3 | goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 1998\u20132002 | clubs6 = [[Austria Vienna]] | caps6 = 134 | goals6 = 65\n| years7         = 2003\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[SV Pasching]] | caps7 = 75 | goals7 = 38\n| years8         = 2005\u20132006 | clubs8 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] | caps8 = 28 | goals8 = 7\n| years9         = 2006\u20132007 | clubs9 = [[SV Pasching]] | caps9 = 30 | goals9 = 11\n| years10        = 2007\u20132010 | clubs10 = [[LASK Linz]] | caps10 = 108 | goals10 = 33\n| years11        = 2011 | clubs11 =[[FC Pasching]] | caps11 = 9 | goals11 = 3\n| totalcaps = 584 | totalgoals = 224\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132005 | nationalteam1 = [[Austria national football team|Austria]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 30 | nationalgoals1 = 6\n| manageryears1  = 2012 | managerclubs1 = ATSV Stadl-Paura (sporting director)\n| manageryears2  = 2012\u20132016 | managerclubs2 = ATSV Stadl-Paura\n| manageryears3  = 2016\u20132018 | managerclubs3 = ASK\u00d6 Oedt\n| manageryears4  = 2019\u2013     | managerclubs4 = ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz\n}}\n\n'''Christian Mayrleb''' (born 8 June 1972) is an Austrian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who is currently employed as the manager of Austrian side ASK\u00d6 Donau Linz.<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/coaches/christian-mayrleb/11167/</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Wels]], [[Upper Austria]], Mayrleb started his professional career at [[Austrian Football First League|Second Division]] side Stahl Linz and [[SV Ried]] before joining [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|First level]] outfit [[VfB Admira Wacker M\u00f6dling|Admira/Wacker]] at the start of the 1994/1995 season. He then played for [[FC Tirol Innsbruck]] where he was snapped up by English [[Premier League]] club [[Sheffield Wednesday]], only to return to Austria after half a season on the subs' bench.\nHe moved to Vienna giants [[Austria Vienna]] for a prolific 4 years before moving on to play for [[SV Pasching]], [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] and ending up in [[Linz]] again with [[LASK|LASK Linz]].\n\nIn November 2006 Mayrleb failed a drug test but was cleared by a League disciplinary panel because no evidence was found he was taking performance-enhancing drugs.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=soccer&id=2668506 Austrian league clears Mayrleb of doping] - ESPN Sports</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHe made his debut for [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in an August 1998 friendly match against [[France national football team|France]] and came on as a substitute in his first six matches for the national team. He scored his first goal two months after his debut game. He earned 29 caps, scoring 6 goals. His last international was a September 2005 World Cup qualification match against [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]].\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[Austrian Bundesliga Top Goalscorer]] (1):'''\n** 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oberliga-a.at/fussball_a/torschutzen_a.htm |title=\u00d6sterreichs Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige |publisher=www.oberliga-a.at |accessdate=2008-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915044827/http://www.oberliga-a.at/fussball_a/torschutzen_a.htm |archivedate=September 15, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|11022}}\n*[http://www.austria-archiv.at/spieler.php?Spieler_ID=30 Profile] - Austria Archive\n*{{NFT player|8668}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|11022-christian-mayrleb}}\n\n{{Austrian Football Bundesliga top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mayrleb, Christian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wels]]\n[[Category:Associa