{"title_page": "KXL-FM", "text_new": "{{for|the original KXL-FM on 95.5 from 1965-1999|KBFF}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KXL-FM\n| image            = File:KXL FMNews101 logo.png\n| city             = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| area             = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| branding         = ''FM News 101 KXL''\n| slogan           = Portland's breaking news, traffic and weather station: Stay connected\n| frequency        = 101.1 [[MHz]]\n| airdate          = September 12, [[1948 in radio|1948]] (as KOIN-FM)\n| format           = [[All-news radio|News]]/[[Talk radio|Talk]]\n| erp              = 100,000 [[watt]]s \n| haat             = {{convert|502|m|sp=us}}\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 26932\n| coordinates      = {{coord|45|30|57.4|N|122|44|3.4|W|region:US-OR_type:landmark_source:FCCInfo-NAD83|display=inline,title}}\n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KOIN-FM (1948&ndash;1977)<br>KYTE-FM (1977&ndash;1979)<br>KLLB (1979&ndash;1983)<br>KRCK (1983&ndash;1985)<br>KYTE-FM (1985&ndash;1989)<br>KKCY (1989&ndash;1990)<br>KUFO (1990&ndash;2001)<br>KUFO-FM (2001&ndash;2010)<br>KUFO (2010&ndash;2011)<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n| affiliations     = [[CBS Radio News]]<br>[[KGW|KGW 8]]\n| owner            = [[Alpha Media]]\n| licensee         = Alpha Media Licensee LLC\n| sister_stations  = [[KBFF]], [[KINK]], [[KUFO (AM)|KUFO]], [[KUPL-FM]], [[KXTG]]\n| webcast          = {{listen live|http://www.kxl.com}}\n| website          = {{url|http://www.kxl.com}}\n}}\n'''KXL-FM''' (101.1 MHz [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is an American commercial [[radio station]] broadcasting a [[news/talk]] format licensed to [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. The station is currently owned by [[Alpha Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=KXL-FM |title=KXL-FM Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.arbitron.com/sip/displaySip.do?surveyID=SU08&band=fm&callLetter=KXL-FM|title=KXL-FM Summer 2008 Station Information Profile|publisher=[[Arbitron]]}}</ref>  Its studios are located in downtown Portland, and its transmitter is in Portland's [[Tualatin Mountains|west hills]]. It is the flagship station for ''[[Lars Larson|The Lars Larson Show]]'' and ''Ground Zero with Clyde Lewis''.\n\n==History==\nThe station signed on the air as '''KOIN-FM''' on September 12, 1948, simulcasting KOIN 970 AM, and began airing [[classical music]] in 1967. The four-hour-long ''KOIN Concert Hall'' was broadcast weekday evenings from 6 to 10 PM, hosted first by Blaine Hanks, then Don Gay.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-september-archive-edition/]</ref> In May 1977, the station changed their call letters to '''KYTE-FM''' and aired a [[top 40]] format as \"The FM Kite\".<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-may-archive-edition/]</ref> On January 5, 1979, KYTE-FM changed their format to [[country music|country]] and then changed the call letters to '''KLLB''' (as \"Country Club 101\").<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/]</ref> On September 4, 1979, KLLB changed format to top 40 rock (as \"KB-101 Rock Deluxe\"), then changed format to [[oldies]] (also as \"KB-101\") a year later.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-september-archive-edition/]</ref> On November 8, 1982, KLLB switched to an album rock format (as \"Rock 101\"); in January 1983, the call letters changed to '''KRCK'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-november-archive-edition/]</ref> On January 3, 1985, KRCK changed their format to [[classical music|classical]] (as \"Classical 101\"), and on February 18, 1985, the call letters changed back to '''KYTE-FM'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/]</ref><ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1985/RR-1985-01-11.pdf]</ref> On January 30, 1989, the station changed its call letters to '''KKCY''' and aired a contemporary [[jazz]] format, branded as \"The City\". (The classical format was moved to KYTE 970 AM.)<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/page/3/]</ref><ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1989/RR-1989-02-03.pdf]</ref>\n\n[[Image:KUFO-FM logo.jpg|left|thumb|KUFO logo (Fri the 29th of December 1989&ndash;Tues the 22nd of March 2011)]]\nOn December 29, 1989, at 5 p.m., after a few days of stunting, KKCY changed to an [[active rock]] format, and on January 23, 1990, the call letters were changed to '''KUFO''', and on August 1, 2001 to '''KUFO-FM'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-december-5/page/3/]</ref><ref name=\"fcc1\">{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=26932&Callsign=KXL-FM |title=KXL-FM Call Sign History |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division |accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KXL 2011 AM-FM logo.png|thumb|right|KXL-FM's logo used during AM/FM simulcast in 2011]]\nIn August 2009, [[CBS Radio]] sold the Portland cluster (including KUFO) to Alpha Broadcasting in an effort to focus more on major market stations.  On October 24, 2009, KUFO began [[stunting (radio)|stunting]] with a \"mothership refueling\" countdown to end at 7 a.m. on October 28th when it re-launched. The actual musical content of KUFO was the same as it was prior to the re-launch; only the personalities changed.<ref>https://formatchange.com/kufo-relaunches/</ref> On September 16, 2010, the call sign reverted to simply '''KUFO'''.\n\nAt 8:47 a.m. on March 15, 2011, KUFO's format was flipped to a simulcast of [[KXTG|KXL]] (750 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]), which broadcasts news and [[Talk radio|talk]] shows.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/32520/kxl-portland-moves-to-fm-replacing-rock-kufo/]</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=130021242238085100 |title=Alpha turns off KUFO\u2019s rock for KXL-FM\u2019s news and talk |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref> On March 22, 2011, the station changed its [[call sign]] to '''KXL-FM''' and billed itself as \"News Radio 101 FM & 750 AM KXL\" (on the same day, the KUFO call letters would move to [[KUFO (AM)|970 AM]]).<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>  It now uses the on air slogan \"FM News 101 KXL\". This is the second FM station in Portland to use the name KXL-FM; it has been used in the past as the callsign by 101.1's sister station 95.5 (now [[KBFF]]).\n\nOn May 25, 2011, at 4 p.m., KXL-FM ended its simulcast with KXL (AM), which flipped to sports as [[KXTG]], \"750 The Game\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/netgnomes/32786/game-over-in-portland/]</ref><ref>[https://formatchange.com/750-kxl-becomes-the-game/]</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2013, KXL-FM announced it had dropped Fox News Radio as an affiliate and picked up [[CBS Radio News]] as its preferred news source.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/101KXL/posts/595574310466481</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Facebook|KXLAM|FM News 101 KXL}}\n*{{Twitter|kxlnews|FM News 101 KXL}}\n*{{FM station data|KXL}}\n*[http://www.kufo.com/ KUFO's goodbye message to listeners]\n\n{{Portland, Oregon Radio}}\n{{News/Talk Radio Stations in Oregon}}\n{{Alpha Media}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1948]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Portland, Oregon|XL-FM]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Alpha Media radio stations]]\n[[Category:American radio stations with a three-letter call sign]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the original KXL-FM on 95.5 from 1965-1999|KBFF}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KXL-FM\n| image            = File:KXL FMNews101 logo.png\n| city             = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| area             = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| branding         = ''FM News 101 KXL''\n| slogan           = Portland's breaking news, traffic and weather station: Stay connected\n| frequency        = 101.1 [[MHz]]\n| airdate          = September 12, [[1948 in radio|1948]] (as KOIN-FM)\n| format           = [[All-news radio|News]]/[[Talk radio|Talk]]\n| erp              = 100,000 [[watt]]s \n| haat             = {{convert|502|m|sp=us}}\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 26932\n| coordinates      = {{coord|45|30|57.4|N|122|44|3.4|W|region:US-OR_type:landmark_source:FCCInfo-NAD83|display=inline,title}}\n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KOIN-FM (1948&ndash;1977)<br>KYTE-FM (1977&ndash;1979)<br>KLLB (1979&ndash;1983)<br>KRCK (1983&ndash;1985)<br>KYTE-FM (1985&ndash;1989)<br>KKCY (1989&ndash;1990)<br>KUFO (1990&ndash;2001)<br>KUFO-FM (2001&ndash;2010)<br>KUFO (2010&ndash;2011)<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n| affiliations     = [[CBS Radio News]]<br>[[KGW|KGW 8]]\n| owner            = [[Alpha Media]]\n| licensee         = Alpha Media Licensee LLC\n| sister_stations  = [[KBFF]], [[KINK]], [[KUFO (AM)|KUFO]], [[KUPL-FM]], [[KXTG]]\n| webcast          = {{listen live|http://www.kxl.com}}\n| website          = {{url|http://www.kxl.com}}\n}}\n'''KXL-FM''' (101.1 MHz [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is an American commercial [[radio station]] broadcasting a [[news/talk]] format licensed to [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. The station is currently owned by [[Alpha Media]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=KXL-FM |title=KXL-FM Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.arbitron.com/sip/displaySip.do?surveyID=SU08&band=fm&callLetter=KXL-FM|title=KXL-FM Summer 2008 Station Information Profile|publisher=[[Arbitron]]}}</ref>  Its studios are located in downtown Portland, and its transmitter is in Portland's [[Tualatin Mountains|west hills]]. It is the flagship station for ''[[Lars Larson|The Lars Larson Show]]'' and ''Ground Zero with Clyde Lewis''.\n\n==History==\nThe station signed on the air as '''KOIN-FM''' on September 12, 1948, simulcasting KOIN 970 AM, and began airing [[classical music]] in 1967. The four-hour-long ''KOIN Concert Hall'' was broadcast weekday evenings from 6 to 10 PM, hosted first by Blaine Hanks, then Don Gay.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-september-archive-edition/]</ref> In May 1977, the station changed their call letters to '''KYTE-FM''' and aired a [[top 40]] format as \"The FM Kite\".<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-may-archive-edition/]</ref> On January 5, 1979, KYTE-FM changed their format to [[country music|country]] and then changed the call letters to '''KLLB''' (as \"Country Club 101\").<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/]</ref> On September 4, 1979, KLLB changed format to top 40 rock (as \"KB-101 Rock Deluxe\"), then changed format to [[oldies]] (also as \"KB-101\") a year later.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-september-archive-edition/]</ref> On November 8, 1982, KLLB switched to an album rock format (as \"Rock 101\"); in January 1983, the call letters changed to '''KRCK'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-november-archive-edition/]</ref> On January 3, 1985, KRCK changed their format to [[classical music|classical]] (as \"Classical 101\"), and on February 18, 1985, the call letters changed back to '''KYTE-FM'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/]</ref><ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1985/RR-1985-01-11.pdf]</ref> On January 30, 1989, the station changed its call letters to '''KKCY''' and aired a contemporary [[jazz]] format, branded as \"The City\". (The classical format was moved to KYTE 970 AM.)<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-january-5/page/3/]</ref><ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1980s/1989/RR-1989-02-03.pdf]</ref>\n\n[[Image:KUFO-FM logo.jpg|left|thumb|KUFO logo (Fri the 29th of December 1989&ndash;Tues the 22nd of March 2011)]]\nOn December 29, 1989, at 5 p.m., after a few days of stunting, KKCY changed to an [[active rock]] format, and on January 23, 1990, the call letters were changed to '''KUFO''', and on August 1, 2001 to '''KUFO-FM'''.<ref>[https://feedback.pdxradio.com/forums/topic/this-day-in-portland-radio-history-december-5/page/3/]</ref><ref name=\"fcc1\">{{cite web |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=26932&Callsign=KXL-FM |title=KXL-FM Call Sign History |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division |accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KXL 2011 AM-FM logo.png|thumb|right|KXL-FM's logo used during AM/FM simulcast in 2011]]\nIn August 2009, [[CBS Radio]] sold the Portland cluster (including KUFO) to Alpha Broadcasting in an effort to focus more on major market stations.  On October 24, 2009, KUFO began [[stunting (radio)|stunting]] with a \"mothership refueling\" countdown to end at 7 a.m. on October 28th when it re-launched. The actual musical content of KUFO was the same as it was prior to the re-launch; only the personalities changed.<ref>https://formatchange.com/kufo-relaunches/</ref> On September 16, 2010, the call sign reverted to simply '''KUFO'''.\n\nAt 8:47 a.m. on March 15, 2011, KUFO's format was flipped to a simulcast of [[KXTG|KXL]] (750 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]), which broadcasts news and [[Talk radio|talk]] shows.<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/32520/kxl-portland-moves-to-fm-replacing-rock-kufo/]</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=130021242238085100 |title=Alpha turns off KUFO\u2019s rock for KXL-FM\u2019s news and talk |work=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=March 15, 2011}}</ref> On March 22, 2011, the station changed its [[call sign]] to '''KXL-FM''' and billed itself as \"News Radio 101 FM & 750 AM KXL.\" (On the same day, the KUFO call letters would move to [[KUFO (AM)|970 AM]].)<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>  It now uses the on air slogan \"FM News 101 KXL\". This is the second FM station in Portland to use the name KXL-FM; it has been used in the past as the callsign by 101.1's sister station 95.5 (now [[KBFF]]).\n\nOn May 25, 2011, at 4 p.m., KXL-FM ended its simulcast with KXL (AM), which flipped to sports as [[KXTG]], \"750 The Game\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/headlines/netgnomes/32786/game-over-in-portland/]</ref><ref>[https://formatchange.com/750-kxl-becomes-the-game/]</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2013, KXL-FM announced it had dropped Fox News Radio as an affiliate and picked up [[CBS Radio News]] as its preferred news source.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/101KXL/posts/595574310466481</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Facebook|KXLAM|FM News 101 KXL}}\n*{{Twitter|kxlnews|FM News 101 KXL}}\n*{{FM station data|KXL}}\n*[http://www.kufo.com/ KUFO's goodbye message to listeners]\n\n{{Portland, Oregon Radio}}\n{{News/Talk Radio Stations in Oregon}}\n{{Alpha Media}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1948]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Portland, Oregon|XL-FM]]\n[[Category:News and talk radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Alpha Media radio stations]]\n[[Category:American radio stations with a three-letter call sign]]\n", "name_user": "DeNoel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Merged orphaned parenthesis into sentence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KXL-FM"}
{"title_page": "Florent Marty", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Florent Marty\n| fullname = Florent Marty\n| image = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|3|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], France\n| height = 1.71 m\n| currentclub  = [[AS Furiani-Agliani|Furiani-Agliani]]\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs1 = [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon B]]\n| caps1 = 28\n| goals1 = 9\n| years2 = 2004\u20132009\n| clubs2 = [[FC Gueugnon|Gueugnon]]\n| caps2 = 112\n| goals2 = 10\n| years3 = 2009\n| clubs3 = [[AS Lyon-Duch\u00e8re|Lyon-Duch\u00e8re]]\n| caps3 = 7\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs4 = [[Amiens SC|Amiens]]\n| caps4 = 27\n| goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs5 = [[AS Vitr\u00e9]]\n| caps5 = 22\n| goals5 = 3\n| years6 = 2011\u20132015\n| clubs6 = [[CA Bastia]]\n| caps6 = 96\n| goals6 = 3\n| years7 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs7 = [[Borgo FC]]\n| caps7 = 20\n| goals7 = 1\n| years8 = 2016\u20132018\n| clubs8 = [[Louhans-Cuiseaux FC|Louhans-Cuiseaux]]\n| caps8 = 44\n| goals8 = 3\n| years9 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs9 = [[AS Furiani-Agliani|Furiani-Agliani]]\n| caps9 = \n| goals9 = \n| pcupdate = 21:39, 21 March 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Florent Marty''' (born 15 March 1984) is a [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for French [[Championnat National]] club [[AS Furiani-Agliani]].\n\nHe signed for [[Championnat National]] side [[Amiens SC]] in the summer of 2009 from [[AS Lyon Duch\u00e8re]].\n\nMarty previously played for [[FC Gueugnon]] in [[Ligue 2]].{{refn|{{LFP|id=marty-florent}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu|18341<!-- -florent-marty -->}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marty, Florent}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:French footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympique Lyonnais player